{"title_page": "Jewish News", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{short description|Free weekly tabloid Jewish newspaper published in the United Kingdom}}\n{{about|the London newspaper||The Jewish News (disambiguation){{!}}The Jewish News}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Jewish News\n| image = Jewish News issue 939.jpg\n| foundation = 1997\n| owner = Leo No\u00e9<ref name=jc-20200212/>\n| format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| publishing_country = United Kingdom\n| website = {{URL|https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com}}\n| editor = [[Richard Ferrer]]\n}}\nThe '''''Jewish News''''' is a free newspaper, established in 1997, that serves the Jewish communities of Greater London \u2013 specifically Middlesex, Hertfordshire and Essex. It is a former ''[[Press Gazette]]'' free newspaper of the year.\n\nIn February 2020, it announced plans to merge with ''The Jewish Chronicle'' but, in April 2020, it went into voluntary liquidation. \n\n==Format and distribution==\nThe ''Jewish News'' is published in [[Tabloid newspaper|tabloid format]] and distributed free of charge. Published every Thursday, the paper provides a weekly mix of local, national and international Jewish news, opinions, features, sport and entertainment.\n\nWith a weekly distribution of 24,518 copies as audited by [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|ABC]] for the period July to December 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abc.org.uk/Products-Services/Product-Page/?tid=13019|title=Product Page - ABC|website=abc.org.uk|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> the paper is the largest Jewish Newspaper in the UK by distribution.<ref>http://www.nrs.co.uk/nrs-print/readership-and-circulation-trends/readership-vs-circulation/</ref> It is available at more than 230 points across the capital including synagogues, shops, schools, community centres and street stands, and {{as of|2019|lc=y}} it had reached its 1100th edition. It is currently under the editorship of former ''[[Daily Mail]]'' journalist and ''[[The Jewish Advocate]]'' editor Richard Ferrer.\n\nIn February 2020 the ''Jewish News'' and ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'' announced plans to merge, subject to raising the necessary finance to support the merger. Combined they print more than 40,000 copies weekly.<ref name=jc-20200212>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-chronicle-and-jewish-news-announce-plans-to-merge-1.496741 |title=Jewish Chronicle and Jewish News announce plans to merge |newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle |date=12 February 2020 |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, ''The Jewish Chronicle'' and ''Jewish News'' announced simultaneously a creditors voluntary liquidation, citing the impact of the coronavirus epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/an-announcement-from-the-jewish-chronicle-1.498949|title=The Jewish Chronicle|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/statement-from-the-board-of-the-jewish-news/|title=Statement from the board of the Jewish News|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|work=Jewish News}}</ref>\n\n==Libel lawsuit and criticism==\nIn February 2018, ''Jewish News'' lost a libel case brought by [[Baroness Warsi]] over allegations that she has sought to excuse the actions of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] terrorists. The article, written by [[Richard Kemp]], also claimed she had objected to action being taken against British Muslims who murder and rape for the group, which Warsi said was \u201cuntrue and offensive\u201d. ''Jewish News'' accepted that the article was false: it apologised and was ordered to pay damages of \u00a320,000 and legal costs.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/baroness-warsi-wins-20000-libel-payout-from-jewish-news-over-article-suggesting-she-excused-actions-of-isis-terrorists/|title=Baroness Warsi wins \u00a320,000 libel payout from Jewish News over article suggesting she excused actions of ISIS terrorists|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|magazine=Press Gazette}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, the ''Jewish News'' Foreign Editor, who had worked for the paper for six years and been editor on a Jewish news TV channel, took personal leave after describing the paper's coverage of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as \"repulsive\" in its use of \"vicious personal phrases\" to \"trash\" a \"dedicated anti-racist\". The Foreign Editor said that the paper had an obsession with the Labour Party, leading to \"overheated rhetoric\", and failed to give a voice to Jews who think differently.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/jewish-news-foreign-editor-takes-leave-after-criticising-papers-coverage-of-labour-anti-semitism-row-in-canary-interview/|title=Jewish News foreign editor takes leave after criticising paper's coverage of Labour anti-Semitism row in Canary interview|last=Forsdick|first=Sam|date=6 August 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|magazine=Press Gazette}}</ref>\n\n== Israel policy conference ==\nIn June 2015, ''Jewish News'' organised its inaugural UK-Israel Shared Strategic Challenges Conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fathomjournal.org/author/jn-bicom-conference-2015/|title=Fathom  \u2013 JN-BICOM 2015 Conference|website=fathomjournal.org|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> Through a series of panels and keynote addresses, the day-long event in Parliament explored issues relating to Israeli politics and the \"two-state solution\", responses to the rise of ISIL and countering radicalisation. Politicians, journalists, government officials and representatives of the major think tanks heard speakers included then Israeli deputy prime minister Silvan Shalom, Opposition Leader Isaac Herzog, Yesh Atid leader Yair Lapid as well as UK Middle east minister Tobias Elwood<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/british-government-official-we-oppose-bds/|title=British government official: We oppose BDS|website=The Times of Israel|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> and Charles Farr, the Home Office's counter terrorism chief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Pro-Israel-British-activists-told-to-fight-back-on-BDS-406955|title=Pro-Israel British activists told to fight back on BDS|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''\n* ''[[Hamodia]]''\n* [[The Jewish Tribune (UK)|''The Jewish Tribune'' (UK)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{URL|https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/}}\n\n{{British Jewry}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1997]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{short description|Free weekly tabloid Jewish newspaper published in the United Kingdom}}\n{{about|the London newspaper||The Jewish News (disambiguation){{!}}The Jewish News}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Jewish News\n| image = Jewish News issue 939.jpg\n| foundation = 1997\n| owner = Leo No\u00e9<ref name=jc-20200212/>\n| format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| publishing_country = United Kingdom\n| website = {{URL|https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com}}\n| editor = [[Richard Ferrer]]\n}}\nThe '''''Jewish News''''' is a free newspaper, established in 1997, that serves the Jewish communities of Greater London \u2013 specifically Middlesex, Hertfordshire and Essex. It is a former ''[[Press Gazette]]'' free newspaper of the year.\n\nIn February 2020, it announced plans to merge with The Jewish Chronicle but, in April 2020, it went into voluntary liquidation. \n\n==Format and distribution==\nThe ''Jewish News'' is published in [[Tabloid newspaper|tabloid format]] and distributed free of charge. Published every Thursday, the paper provides a weekly mix of local, national and international Jewish news, opinions, features, sport and entertainment.\n\nWith a weekly distribution of 24,518 copies as audited by [[Audit Bureau of Circulations (UK)|ABC]] for the period July to December 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abc.org.uk/Products-Services/Product-Page/?tid=13019|title=Product Page - ABC|website=abc.org.uk|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> the paper is the largest Jewish Newspaper in the UK by distribution.<ref>http://www.nrs.co.uk/nrs-print/readership-and-circulation-trends/readership-vs-circulation/</ref> It is available at more than 230 points across the capital including synagogues, shops, schools, community centres and street stands, and {{as of|2019|lc=y}} it had reached its 1100th edition. It is currently under the editorship of former ''[[Daily Mail]]'' journalist and ''[[The Jewish Advocate]]'' editor Richard Ferrer.\n\nIn February 2020 the ''Jewish News'' and ''[[Jewish Chronicle]]'' announced plans to merge, subject to raising the necessary finance to support the merger. Combined they print more than 40,000 copies weekly.<ref name=jc-20200212>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/jewish-chronicle-and-jewish-news-announce-plans-to-merge-1.496741 |title=Jewish Chronicle and Jewish News announce plans to merge |newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle |date=12 February 2020 |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, ''The Jewish Chronicle'' and ''Jewish News'' announced simultaneously a creditors voluntary liquidation, citing the impact of the coronavirus epidemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/an-announcement-from-the-jewish-chronicle-1.498949|title=The Jewish Chronicle|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|work=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/statement-from-the-board-of-the-jewish-news/|title=Statement from the board of the Jewish News|date=8 April 2020|accessdate=8 April 2020|work=Jewish News}}</ref>\n\n==Libel lawsuit and criticism==\nIn February 2018, ''Jewish News'' lost a libel case brought by [[Baroness Warsi]] over allegations that she has sought to excuse the actions of [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] terrorists. The article, written by [[Richard Kemp]], also claimed she had objected to action being taken against British Muslims who murder and rape for the group, which Warsi said was \u201cuntrue and offensive\u201d. ''Jewish News'' accepted that the article was false: it apologised and was ordered to pay damages of \u00a320,000 and legal costs.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/baroness-warsi-wins-20000-libel-payout-from-jewish-news-over-article-suggesting-she-excused-actions-of-isis-terrorists/|title=Baroness Warsi wins \u00a320,000 libel payout from Jewish News over article suggesting she excused actions of ISIS terrorists|last=Mayhew|first=Freddy|date=26 February 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|magazine=Press Gazette}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, the ''Jewish News'' Foreign Editor, who had worked for the paper for six years and been editor on a Jewish news TV channel, took personal leave after describing the paper's coverage of [[Jeremy Corbyn]] as \"repulsive\" in its use of \"vicious personal phrases\" to \"trash\" a \"dedicated anti-racist\". The Foreign Editor said that the paper had an obsession with the Labour Party, leading to \"overheated rhetoric\", and failed to give a voice to Jews who think differently.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.pressgazette.co.uk/jewish-news-foreign-editor-takes-leave-after-criticising-papers-coverage-of-labour-anti-semitism-row-in-canary-interview/|title=Jewish News foreign editor takes leave after criticising paper's coverage of Labour anti-Semitism row in Canary interview|last=Forsdick|first=Sam|date=6 August 2018|accessdate=2 September 2019|magazine=Press Gazette}}</ref>\n\n== Israel policy conference ==\nIn June 2015, ''Jewish News'' organised its inaugural UK-Israel Shared Strategic Challenges Conference.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fathomjournal.org/author/jn-bicom-conference-2015/|title=Fathom  \u2013 JN-BICOM 2015 Conference|website=fathomjournal.org|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> Through a series of panels and keynote addresses, the day-long event in Parliament explored issues relating to Israeli politics and the \"two-state solution\", responses to the rise of ISIL and countering radicalisation. Politicians, journalists, government officials and representatives of the major think tanks heard speakers included then Israeli deputy prime minister Silvan Shalom, Opposition Leader Isaac Herzog, Yesh Atid leader Yair Lapid as well as UK Middle east minister Tobias Elwood<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/british-government-official-we-oppose-bds/|title=British government official: We oppose BDS|website=The Times of Israel|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref> and Charles Farr, the Home Office's counter terrorism chief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Pro-Israel-British-activists-told-to-fight-back-on-BDS-406955|title=Pro-Israel British activists told to fight back on BDS|website=The Jerusalem Post {{!}} JPost.com|access-date=2016-05-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''\n* ''[[Hamodia]]''\n* [[The Jewish Tribune (UK)|''The Jewish Tribune'' (UK)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{URL|https://jewishnews.timesofisrael.com/}}\n\n{{British Jewry}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1997]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jewish_News"}
{"title_page": "Walter of Pontoise", "text_new": "{{Other people|Gaultier}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name= Saint Walter of Pontoise  \n|birth_date= {{circa|1030}}\n|death_date= Good Friday {{circa|1099}}\n|feast_day= [[March 23]]\n|venerated_in= [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|image= Pontoise Cath\u00e9drale Saint-Maclou110296.JPG\n|imagesize= 250px\n|caption= \n|birth_place= Andainville, Picardy\n|death_place=\n|titles= \n|beatified_date=  \n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=1153\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=[[Hugh de Boves]], the [[Archbishop of Rouen]] \n|attributes= \n|patronage=Prisoners; prisoners of war; vintners; invoked against job-related stress<ref>Annette Sandoval, ''The Directory of Saints: A Concise Guide to Patron Saints'' (Signet, 1997), 226.</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.stwalterchurch.com/Patron-St__Walter/patron-st__walter.html Patron-St. Walter<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n|major_shrine= \n|suppressed_date=\n|issues= \n}}\n'''Saint Walter of Pontoise''' ({{lang-fr|Saint Gautier, Gaultier, Gaucher}}; {{circa|1030}} \u2013 {{circa|1099}}) was a [[France|French]] [[saint]] of the eleventh century.  Born at [[Andainville]],<ref name=\"stpatrickdc\">[http://www.saintpatrickdc.org/ss/0408.shtml Saint of the Day, May 8: ''Walter of Pontoise''] ''SaintPatrickDC.org.'' Retrieved 2012-03-05.</ref> he was a professor of [[philosophy]] and [[rhetoric]] before becoming a [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] monk at [[Rebais]] (diocese of [[Meaux]]).  A story told of him is that while a novice, Walter took pity on an inmate at the monastery prison, and helped the prisoner to escape.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n \n[[Philip I of France|Philip I]] appointed him [[abbot]] of a new foundation at [[Pontoise]], despite Walter's protestations.  The foundation of Pontoise was initially dedicated to [[Saint Germanus of Paris]] but then was dedicated to [[Martin of Tours|Saint Martin]].  The discipline at this new foundation was lax, and Walter fled the house several times to avoid this responsibility.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/46690 San Walter (Gualtiero, Gualterio) di S. Martino di Pontoise<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nWalter left his position at Pontoise to become a monk at [[Cluny Abbey|Cluny]] under [[Hugh of Cluny|Hugh]] but he was forced to return to Pontoise.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  A story told of him was that he once took the road to [[Touraine]] and hid himself on an island in the [[Loire]], before being led back to the abbey.<ref name=\"stpatrickdc\"/>  He also escaped to an oratory near [[Tours]] dedicated to [[Cosmas and Damian]] before being recognized by a [[pilgrim]] there.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAfter being forced to return again, this time Walter decided to go to [[Rome]] to appeal directly to the [[pope]].  Walter gave [[Pope Gregory VII]] his written resignation, but Gregory ordered him to assume his responsibilities as abbot and never leave again.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nThereafter, he campaigned against the abuses and corruptions of his fellow Benedictines, and was beaten and imprisoned.  He resumed his work after being released.  He founded, in 1094, at [[Berteaucourt-les-Dames]] near [[Amiens]], a monastery for women, with the assistance of Godelinda and Elvige (also spelled Godelende and H\u00e9leguide).<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[http://pagesperso-orange.fr/foure-bouchon-histoire/seigneurs/berteaucourt/ab_berteaubulle.htm Abbaye de Berteaucourt<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Veneration==\n\nWalter was buried in the abbey at Pontoise.  He was canonized by Hugh the [[Archbishop of Rouen]] in 1153, and was the last saint in [[Western Europe]] to have been canonized by an authority other than the pope.<ref name=smith>[https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofchri01smituoft/dictionaryofchri01smituoft_djvu.txt William Smith, Samuel Cheetham, ''A Dictionary of Christian Antiquities'' (Murray, 1875), 283.]</ref><ref>[http://www.saint-mike.org/library/papal_library/AlexanderIII/biography.html Biography \u2013 Pope Alexander III \u2013 The Papal Library<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  \u201cThe last case of canonization by a metropolitan is said to have been that of St. Gaultier, or Gaucher, abbat [sic] of Pontoise, by the Archbishop of Rouen, A.D. 1153.  A decree of [[Pope Alexander III]], A.D. 1170, gave the prerogative to the pope thenceforth, so far as the Western Church was concerned.\u201d<ref name=smith/>\n\nDuring the [[French Revolution]], his body was [[translation (relics)|translated]] to the cemetery of Pontoise, and was later lost.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  The College of Saint Martin of Pontoise, now an [[Oratory of Jesus|Oratorian]] foundation, celebrates his feast.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-walter-of-pontoise/ Walter of Pontoise]\n*[http://catholicprwire.com/saints/saint.php?saint_id=596 Walter of Pontoise]\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/46690 San Walter (Gualtiero, Gualterio) di S. Martino di Pontoise]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walter Of Pontoise}}\n[[Category:French Benedictines]]\n[[Category:Benedictine abbots]]\n[[Category:Benedictine saints]]\n[[Category:Medieval French saints]]\n[[Category:French abbots]]\n[[Category:1030 births]]\n[[Category:1099 deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Christian saints]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Gaultier}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name= Saint Walter of Pontoise  \n|birth_date= {{circa|1030}}\n|death_date= Good Friday {{circa|1099}}\n|feast_day= [[March 23]]\n|venerated_in= [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|image= Pontoise Cath\u00e9drale Saint-Maclou110296.JPG\n|imagesize= 250px\n|caption= \n|birth_place= Andainville, Picardy\n|death_place=\n|titles= \n|beatified_date=  \n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=1153\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=[[Hugh de Boves]], the [[Archbishop of Rouen]] \n|attributes= \n|patronage=Prisoners; prisoners of war; vintners; invoked against job-related stress<ref>Annette Sandoval, ''The Directory of Saints: A Concise Guide to Patron Saints'' (Signet, 1997), 226.</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.stwalterchurch.com/Patron-St__Walter/patron-st__walter.html Patron-St. Walter<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n|major_shrine= \n|suppressed_date=\n|issues= \n}}\n'''Saint Walter of Pontoise''' ({{lang-fr|Saint Gautier, Gaultier, Gaucher}}; {{circa|1030}} \u2013 {{circa|1099}}) was a [[France|French]] [[saint]] of the eleventh century.  Born at [[Andainville]],<ref name=\"stpatrickdc\">[http://www.saintpatrickdc.org/ss/0408.shtml Saint of the Day, May 8: ''Walter of Pontoise''] ''SaintPatrickDC.org.'' Retrieved 2012-03-05.</ref> he was a professor of [[philosophy]] and [[rhetoric]] before becoming a [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] monk at [[Rebais]] (diocese of [[Meaux]]).  A story told of him is that while a novice, Walter took pity on an inmate at the monastery prison, and helped the prisoner to escape.<ref name=autogenerated3 />\n \n[[Philip I of France|Philip I]] appointed him [[abbot]] of a new foundation at [[Pontoise]], despite Walter's protestations.  The foundation of Pontoise was initially dedicated to [[Saint Germanus of Paris]] but then was dedicated to [[Martin of Tours|Saint Martin]].  The discipline at this new foundation was lax, and Walter fled the house several times to avoid this responsibility.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/46690 San Walter (Gualtiero, Gualterio) di S. Martino di Pontoise<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nWalter left his position at Pontoise to become a monk at [[Cluny Abbey|Cluny]] under [[Hugh of Cluny|Hugh]] but he was forced to return to Pontoise.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  A story told of him was that he once took the road to [[Touraine]] and hid himself on an island in the [[Loire]], before being led back to the abbey.<ref name=\"stpatrickdc\"/>  He also escaped to an oratory near [[Tours]] dedicated to [[Cosmas and Damian]] before being recognized by a [[pilgrim]] there.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAfter being forced to return again, this time Walter decided to go to [[Rome]] to appeal directly to the [[Pope]].  Walter gave [[Pope Gregory VII]] his written resignation, but Gregory ordered him to assume his responsibilities as abbot and never leave again.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nThereafter, he campaigned against the abuses and corruptions of his fellow Benedictines, and was beaten and imprisoned.  He resumed his work after being released.  He founded, in 1094, at [[Berteaucourt-les-Dames]] near [[Amiens]], a monastery for women, with the assistance of Godelinda and Elvige (also spelled Godelende and H\u00e9leguide).<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>[http://pagesperso-orange.fr/foure-bouchon-histoire/seigneurs/berteaucourt/ab_berteaubulle.htm Abbaye de Berteaucourt<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Veneration==\n\nWalter was buried in the abbey at Pontoise.  He was canonized by Hugh the [[Archbishop of Rouen]] in 1153, and was the last saint in [[Western Europe]] to have been canonized by an authority other than the Pope.<ref name=smith>[https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofchri01smituoft/dictionaryofchri01smituoft_djvu.txt William Smith, Samuel Cheetham, ''A Dictionary of Christian Antiquities'' (Murray, 1875), 283.]</ref><ref>[http://www.saint-mike.org/library/papal_library/AlexanderIII/biography.html Biography \u2013 Pope Alexander III \u2013 The Papal Library<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  \u201cThe last case of canonization by a metropolitan is said to have been that of St. Gaultier, or Gaucher, abbat [sic] of Pontoise, by the Archbishop of Rouen, A.D. 1153.  A decree of [[Pope Alexander III]], A.D. 1170, gave the prerogative to the pope thenceforth, so far as the Western Church was concerned.\u201d<ref name=smith/>\n\nDuring the [[French Revolution]], his body was [[translation (relics)|translated]] to the cemetery of Pontoise, and was later lost.<ref name=autogenerated1 />  The College of Saint Martin of Pontoise, now an [[Oratory of Jesus|Oratorian]] foundation, celebrates his feast.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-walter-of-pontoise/ Walter of Pontoise]\n*[http://catholicprwire.com/saints/saint.php?saint_id=596 Walter of Pontoise]\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.santiebeati.it/dettaglio/46690 San Walter (Gualtiero, Gualterio) di S. Martino di Pontoise]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walter Of Pontoise}}\n[[Category:French Benedictines]]\n[[Category:Benedictine abbots]]\n[[Category:Benedictine saints]]\n[[Category:Medieval French saints]]\n[[Category:French abbots]]\n[[Category:1030 births]]\n[[Category:1099 deaths]]\n[[Category:11th-century Christian saints]]\n", "name_user": "Tepeyachermit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_of_Pontoise"}
{"title_page": "Malappuram (Lok Sabha constituency)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox Lok Sabha Constituency\n |image             = [[File:Malappuram Lok Sabha Constituency.jpg|Map of Malappuram Parliament Constituency]]\n\n |Existence         = 2009\u2013present\n |Reservation       = None\n |CurrentMPParty    = [[Indian Union Muslim League|IUML]]\n |CurrentMP         = [[P. K. Kunhalikutty]]\n |ElectedByYear     = [[2019 Indian general election|2019]]\n |State             = [[Kerala]]\n |Successful Party  = [[Indian Union Muslim League]] (3 times)\n |AssemblyConstituencies =33. [[Kondotty (State Assembly constituency)|Kondotty]]<br>37. [[Manjeri (State Assembly constituency)|Manjeri]]<br>38. [[Perinthalmanna (State Assembly constituency)|Perinthalmanna]]<br>39. [[Mankada (State Assembly constituency)|Mankada]]<br>40. [[Malappuram (State Assembly constituency)|Malappuram]]<br>41. [[Vengara (State Assembly constituency)|Vengara]]<br>42. [[Vallikkunnu (State Assembly constituency)|Vallikkunnu]]\n |Electorate        = 13,69,878 (2019)\n}}\n'''Malappuram Lok Sabha constituency''' ({{lang-ml|\u0d2e\u0d32\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d41\u0d31\u0d02 \u0d32\u0d4b\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d38\u0d2d\u0d3e \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d2f\u0d4b\u0d1c\u0d15 \u0d2e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d21\u0d32\u0d02}}) is one of the 20 [[Lok Sabha]] (parliamentary) constituencies in [[Kerala]] state in southern [[India]].\n\n==Assembly segments==\n\nMalappuram Lok Sabha constituency is composed of the following assembly segments:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"500px\"  style=\"border-collapse: collapse; border: 2px #666666 solid; font-size: x-big; font-family: API PHONETIQUE\"\n!width=\"50px\" style=\"font-size:75%\"|Constituency number\n!width=\"150px\" style=\"font-size:95%\"|Name\n!width=\"100px\" style=\"font-size:75%\"|Reserved for ([[Dalit|SC]]/[[Adivasi|ST]]/None)\n!width=\"150px\" style=\"font-size:95%\"|District\n|-\n|33\n|[[Kondotty (State Assembly constituen