{"title_page": "Marion Barry", "text_new": "{{about|the former mayor of Washington, D.C|his son|Marion Christopher Barry|the former U.S. House member|Robert Marion Berry|the fruit grown in Oregon|Marionberry}}\n{{short description|20th and 21s-century American politician and former mayor of Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Marion Barry\n|image        = Crop of Marion Barry Vincent Gray.jpg{{!}}border\n|office       = 2nd and 4th [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]\n|term_start   = January 2, 1995\n|term_end     = January 2, 1999\n|predecessor  = [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]\n|successor    = [[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams]]\n|term_start1  = January 2, 1979\n|term_end1    = January 2, 1991\n|predecessor1 = [[Walter Washington]]\n|successor1   = [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]\n|office2      = Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />from [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]]\n|term_start2  = January 2, 2005\n|term_end2    = November 23, 2014\n|predecessor2 = [[Sandy Allen (D.C. Council)|Sandy Allen]]\n|successor2   = [[LaRuby May]]\n|term_start3  = January 2, 1993\n|term_end3    = January 2, 1995\n|predecessor3 = [[Wilhelmina Rolark]]\n|successor3   = [[Eydie Whittington]]\n|office4      = Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />At-Large\n|term_start4  = January 2, 1975\n|term_end4    = January 2, 1979\n|predecessor4 = Position established\n|successor4   = [[John L. Ray|John Ray]]\n|office5      = Chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]]\n|term_start5  = 1960\n|term_end5    = 1961\n|predecessor5 = Position established\n|successor5   = [[Charles McDew]]\n|birth_name   = Marion Barry Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1936|03|6}}\n|birth_place  = [[Itta Bena, Mississippi]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2014|11|23|1936|03|6}}\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[Congressional Cemetery]]\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Blantie Evans (1962\u20131964)<br />Mary Treadwell (1972\u20131977)<br />Effi Slaughter (1978\u20131993)<br />Cora Masters (1993\u20132014)\n|children     = [[Marion Christopher Barry|Marion]] (with Slaughter)\n|education    = [[LeMoyne\u2013Owen College|LeMoyne-Owen College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[Fisk University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])<br />[[University of Kansas|University of Kansas, Lawrence]]<br />[[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee, Knoxville]]\n}}\n'''Marion Shepilov Barry''' (born '''Marion Barry Jr.'''; March 6, 1936&nbsp;\u2013 November 23, 2014)<ref name=nytimesobit>{{cite news|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78 |first= David|last=Stout|date=November 23, 2014|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0}}</ref> was an American politician who served as the second [[mayor of the District of Columbia]] from 1979 to 1991, and again as the fourth mayor from 1995 to 1999. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], Barry had served three tenures on the [[Council of the District of Columbia]], representing as an at-large member from 1975 to 1979 and in [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]] from 1993 to 1995, and again from 2005 to 2014. In the 1960s he was involved in the [[civil rights movement]], first as a member of the [[Nashville Student Movement]] and then serving as the first chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] (SNCC).\n\nBarry came to national prominence as mayor of the national capital, the first prominent civil rights activist to become chief executive of a major American city.<ref name=barras>{{cite book |title=The Last of the Black Emperors: The Hollow Comeback of Marion Barry in a New Age of Black Leaders |last=Barras |first=Jonetta Rose |year=1998 |publisher=Bancroft Press |isbn=0-9631246-6-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/lastofblackemper00barr }}</ref> He gave the presidential nomination speech for [[Jesse Jackson]] at the [[1984 Democratic National Convention]]. His celebrity was transformed into international notoriety in January 1990, when he was videotaped during a sting operation smoking [[crack cocaine]] and was arrested by [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) officials on [[Federal drug policy of the United States|drug charges]]. The arrest and subsequent trial precluded Barry from seeking re-election, and he served six months in a [[List of United States federal prisons|federal prison]]. After his release, he was elected to the Council of the District of Columbia in 1992. He was elected again as mayor in 1994, serving from 1995 to 1999.\n\nDespite his history of political and legal controversies, Barry was a popular and influential figure in [[Washington, D.C.]] The [[Alternative newspaper|alternative weekly]] ''[[Washington City Paper]]'' nicknamed him \"Mayor for life\", a designation that remained long after Barry left the mayoralty.<ref name=dreamcity>{{cite book |title=Dream City: Race, Power, and the Decline of Washington, D.C. |last=Jaffe |first=Harry S. |author2=Tom Sherwood |year=1994 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=0-671-76846-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/dreamcityracepow00jaff }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' once stated that \"to understand the District of Columbia, one must understand Marion Barry\".<ref name=making>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry: Making of a Mayor. |newspaper=Washington Post |date=May 21, 1998 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barry.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==1936\u20131954: Early life==\nMarion Barry was born from his mother's womb.  the third child Degorbinaforgo Nutswock and Marion Guts .<ref name=comeback>{{cite news |title=The 1994 Campaign: The Comeback Man in the News: From Disgrace to 'Amazing Grace': Marion Shepilov Barry Jr. |work=The New York Times |date=September 14, 1994 |first=Michael |last=Janofsky |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02E3DC153BF937A2575AC0A962958260}}</ref><ref name=just>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Just Wants to Be Loved |first=Arthur S. |last=Brisbane |date=April 26, 1987 |page=W20 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/87prof.htm}}</ref><ref name=cummings /> His father died when he was four years old, and a year later his mother moved the family to [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=just /> where her employment prospects were better.<ref name=cummings /> His mother married David Cummings, a butcher, and together they raised eight children.<ref name= nytimesobit /> Growing up on Latham Street near [[Memphis Parkway System|South Parkway]], Marion Barry attended Florida Elementary and graduated from [[Booker T. Washington High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Booker T. Washington High]].\n\nThe first time Barry noticed racial issues was when he had to walk to school while the white students were assigned a school bus to ride. The schools were segregated, as were public facilities.<ref name=oralhistory /> He had a number of jobs as a child, including picking cotton, delivering and selling newspapers, and bagging groceries.<ref name=just /> While in high school, Barry worked as a waiter at the [[American Legion]] post and, at age 17,<ref>January 11, 1954 \u2013 Troop 184 of the [[Chickasaw Council]] (#558)</ref> earned the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]].<ref name=just /><ref name=activist>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry: The Activist Denies He's Changed |first=Milton |last=Coleman |work=Washington Post |date=January 2, 1979 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/79change.htm}}</ref>\n\nMarion Barry first began his spirit of civil rights activism when he was a paperboy in Memphis. The paper he worked for organized a contest in which any boys who gained 15 new customers could win a trip to New Orleans. Barry and a couple of the other black paperboys reached the quota of 15 new customers yet were not allowed to go on the trip to New Orleans, a segregated city. The paper said it could not afford to hire two buses to satisfy Mississippi's segregation rules. Barry decided to boycott his paper route until they agreed to send the black paperboys on a trip. After the paper offered the black paperboys a chance to go to [[St. Louis, Missouri]] on a trip, because it was not a segregated city, Barry resumed his paper route.<ref name=oralhistory>{{cite news |title=Telling Their Stories: Oral History Archives Project |date=March 21, 2011 |url=http://www.tellingstories.org/mccomb/fullmovies/marion-barry/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104165855/http://www.tellingstories.org/mccomb/fullmovies/marion-barry/index.html |archivedate=November 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==1955\u20131970: Education and civil rights activism==\n===Undergraduate studies at LeMoyne College ===\nBarry attended [[LeMoyne\u2013Owen College]], in Memphis, graduating in 1958.<ref name=comeback /> In his junior year, the racial injustices he had seen started to come together. He and his friends went to a segregated fairground in Memphis, and went at a time reserved for whites, because they wanted to see the science exhibit. When they were close to the exhibit, a policeman stopped them and asked them to leave. Barry and his friends left without protest. At that time, Barry did not know much about his race, or why they were treated poorly, but he resented the incident. Barry became more active in the [[NAACP]] chapter at LeMoyne-Owens, serving as president.<ref name=blackleaders>Rose, Thomas \"Black Leaders: Then and Now; A Personal History of Students who Led the Civil Rights Movement in the 1960s\u2014And What Happened to Them\" p. 47-52</ref> It is sometimes said that his ardent support of the civil rights movement earned him the nickname \"Shep\", in reference to Soviet politician [[Dmitri Shepilov]], and then Barry began using Shepilov as his middle name.<ref name=comeback /> But Barry stated in his autobiography that he chose the name with regard to his middle initial S, which had initially stood for nothing,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78|last=Stout|first=David|date=November 23, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> after having found Shepilov's name in newspapers: \"I had picked out \"Shepilov\" as a middle name because it was the only one that I knew and liked\".<ref>Barry, Marion, and Omar Tyree. ''Mayor For Life : The Incredible Story of Marion Barry, Jr''. New York: Strebor Books, 2014. P. 36</ref>\n\nIn 1958, at LeMoyne-Owens, he criticized a college trustee for remarks he felt were demeaning to African Americans, for which he was nearly expelled.<ref name=just /> While a senior and the president of the NAACP chapter, Barry heard of Walter Chandler\u2014the only white member on LeMoyne-Owen's board of trustees\u2014making comments that black people should be treated as a \"younger brother not as an adult\". Barry wrote a letter to LeMoyne's president objecting to the comments and asking if Walter Chandler could be removed from the board.<ref name=demdestiny>Walters, Ronald \"Democratic Destiny and The District of Columbia\" p. 61-69</ref> A friend of Barry's was the editor of the school newspaper, the ''Magician'', and told Barry to run the letter in the paper. From there, the letter made it to the front page of Memphis' conservative morning paper.<ref name=oralhistory />\n\n===Master's degree, Nashville Student Movement, SNCC===\n{{Alpha Phi Alpha articles}}\nBarry earned an M.S. in [[organic chemistry]] from [[Fisk University]]<ref name=comeback /> in 1960. He was a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity.<ref name=alphaconvention>{{cite news |title= Alpha's National Convention in D.C. |work= The Baltimore Afro-American |date= August 18, 1979 |page= 12 |id= {{ProQuest|532444541}} }}</ref> While in graduate school at Fisk, Barry was arrested several times while participating in the [[Nashville sit-ins]] to desegregate lunch counters and other Civil Rights Movement events.<ref name=blackleaders /> After graduating from Fisk, Barry continued to work in the Civil Rights Movement, focusing on the elimination of the [[racial segregation]] of bus passengers.\n\nIn 1960, Barry was elected as the first chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] (SNCC). He helped develop an organizing project in [[McComb, Mississippi]]. The project was both a voter registration and a direct action endeavor. Barry said he and other activists lived with the local people in order to stay safe, as well as to learn what it was like to live there. They could use that information to organize the members of the SNCC accordingly.<ref name=oralhistory />\n\n===Doctoral studies===\nBarry began doctoral studies at the [[University of Kansas]], but soon quit the program.<ref name=just /> He contemplated law school to help with his activism, but decided against it, because the delayed admission would mean that he would have to take a year off from school. Had he taken a year off, there was a chance of his being drafted into the military, and he did not want to be drafted.\n\nHe decided to go to the University of Tennessee where he was awarded a graduate fellowship. Despite being located in the South, the University of Tennessee was an integrated educational institution, a new experience for Barry.<ref name=blackleaders /> He began doctoral [[chemistry]] studies at the [[University of Tennessee]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]], the only African American in the program.<ref name=just /> He learned that he was prohibited from tutoring white children, and his wife Blantie Evans was not allowed to work at the white school.<ref name=just /> He quit the program in favor of his new duties at SNCC.\n\nIn the Spring of 1964, he attended a conference in Nashville and became one of the founders of the Southern Student Organizing Committee (SSOC).\n\n===Working for SNCC===\nAs head of SNCC, Barry led protests against racial segregation and discrimination.<ref name=just /><ref>{{cite news |title= Chicago |work= The Washington Post |date= June 26, 1964 |page= A10 |agency=Associated Press |id= {{ProQuest|142223020}} }}</ref> After he left McComb, Barry's lobbied the state legislatures to try to convince them to vote to make the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] (MFDP) the recognized Democratic party of Mississippi in the [[1964 Democratic National Convention]]. In a protest of their continuing disenfranchisement, African Americans had organized this party to prove that blacks wanted to vote and conducted a trial election. Barry slept on the boardwalk in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]] the night after speaking to the [[New Jersey Legislature]].<ref name=oralhistory />\n\nAfter he left the New York legislature, [[James Forman]] asked Barry to go to Washington, D.C. to manage SNCC's office. At the time, over half of the population of Washington D.C. was black, and they had no political representation in Congress, as the capital was considered a different kind of jurisdiction.<ref name=demdestiny />\n\nIn 1965, Barry and Evans<ref>{{cite news |title= Marion Barry |work= The Times |location= London, England |date= November 24, 2014 |page= 42 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=151CD80535948D80&p_docnum=1&p_queryname=21}}</ref> moved to Washington, D.C., to open a local chapter of SNCC. He was deeply involved in coordinating peaceful street demonstrations as well as a boycott to protest bus fare increases. Barry organized rides to work for those who needed them. The boycott cost the bus line thousands of dollars, and Barry proved his ability to organize.<ref name=activist /><ref name=blackleaders /><ref>{{cite news |title=SNCC May Call Bus Boycott |work=Baltimore Afro-American |date=January 1, 1966 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aOhfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AAMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=5641,38921&dq=marion-barry&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nHe also served as the leader of the Free D.C. Movement, strongly supporting increased [[District of Columbia home rule|home rule]], as a Congressional committee exercised administrative rule over the district.<ref name=activist /><ref name=frustrating>{{cite news |title=Barry Finds Home Rule a Frustrating Battle |first=Dan |last=Morgan |work=The Washington Post|date=July 25, 1966 |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A47599-2004Jul13.html}}</ref> Barry quit SNCC in 1967, when [[H. Rap Brown]] became chairman of the group.<ref name=activist /> In 1967, Barry and Mary Treadwell co-founded Pride, Inc., a Department of Labor-funded program to provide job training to unemployed black men.<ref name=just /><ref name=prepareforwork>{{cite news |title= 600 Pride, Inc., Volunteers Prepare for Work |first= Hollie I. |last= West |work= The Washington Post |date= August 6, 1967 |page= C2 |id= {{ProQuest|143061918}} }}</ref> The group employed hundreds of teenagers to clean littered streets and alleys in the district.<ref name=prepareforwork /><ref>{{cite news |title=Capital's Eyesores Falls to Pride, Inc |date=August 9, 1967 |work=The Fort Scott Tribune |location=Fort Scott, Kansas |agency=Associated Press |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U9gfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LtkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=986,4897448&dq=marion-barry+pride-inc&hl=en}}</ref> Barry and Treadwell had met while students at Fisk University, and they later met again while picketing in front of the Washington Gas Light Company.<ref name=marries>{{cite news |title= Marion Barry Marries |work= The Washington Post |first= Sally |last= Quinn |date= May 27, 1972 |page= B3 |id= {{ProQuest|148282440}} }}</ref>\n\nBarry and Treadwell married in 1972.<ref name=marries /> They separated five years later.<ref name=just />\n\nBarry was active in the aftermath of the [[1968 Washington, D.C. riots]] that followed the [[assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.]] in Memphis. He organized through Pride Inc. a program of free food distribution for poor black residents whose homes and neighborhoods had been destroyed in the rioting. Barry convinced the [[Giant-Landover|Giant Food]] supermarket chain to donate food, and he spent a week driving trucks and delivering food throughout the city's housing projects. He also became a board member of the city's Economic Development Committee, helping to route federal funds and venture capital to black-owned businesses that were struggling to recover from the riots.<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nWhen President [[Richard Nixon]] declared July 21, 1969, National Day of Participation in honor of the moon landing by [[Apollo 11]], Barry criticized him. Barry believed that Dr. [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] deserved a national honor day on his birthday, which Nixon had opposed.<ref name=apollo>{{cite news |title= Barry Slams Apollo 11 Mission |first= Vincent |last= Paka |work= The Washington Post |page= A9 |date= July 19, 1969 |id= {{ProQuest|147633287}} }}</ref> Said Barry, \"Why should blacks feel elated when we see men eating on the moon when millions of blacks and poor whites don't have enough money to buy food here on earth?\"<ref name=apollo />\n\n==1971\u20131974: D.C. Board of Education==\nIn 1971, Barry announced his candidacy for [[at-large]] member of the [[board of education|school board]], running against the incumbent, Anita L. Allen.<ref name=barbs>{{cite news |title= Barry-Allen Barbs Fly in School Race |first1= Lawrence |last1= Feinberg |first2= Ivan C. |last2= Brandon |work= The Washington Post |date= September 10, 1971 |page= C1 |id= {{ProQuest|148180978}} }}</ref><ref name=sixseats>{{cite news |title= 31 File Petitions for Six Seats on Washington School Board |date= September 20, 1971 |page= C2 |work= The Washington Post |id= {{ProQuest|148003283}} }}</ref> Barry said he wanted to steer the school board back to the \"issues of education\" and away from problems of personalities.<ref name=barbs /> Barry defeated Allen, with 58 percent of the vote to Allen's 34 percent.<ref name=allen>{{cite news |title= Mrs. Allen, Allies Lose D.C. Vote |first= Richard E. |last= Prince |work= The Washington Post |date= November 3, 1971 |id= {{ProQuest|148122881}} }}</ref>\n\nAfter Barry was seated in 1972,<ref name=comeback /> he was unanimously elected as president of the board.<ref>{{cite news |title= School Board Elects Barry As President |first= Irna |last= Moore |date= January 25, 1972 |work= The Washington Post |id= {{ProQuest|148204550}} }}</ref> He served as board president for two years, reorganizing the school system's finances and building consensus on the board.\n\nIn response to the 1972 [[blaxploitation]] film ''[[Super Fly (1972 film)|Super Fly]]'', Barry quickly formed a protest group named Blacks Against Narcotics and Genocide (BANG). Barry said the film was harmful to black youth, and that it glorified drug abuse. BANG called for a boycott of the film.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Yts9jEMop0C&pg=PA156 |page=156 |title=At a Theater Or Drive-In Near You: The History, Culture and Politics of the American Exploitation Film |last=Clark |first=Randall |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=1995 |isbn=0815319517 |edition=revised}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19720922&id=CrczAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YTIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=3320,1681468 |date=September 22, 1972 |last=Tully |first=Andrew |newspaper=Lodi News-Sentinel |title=Capital Fare: It only hurts black kids |page=6 |access-date=March 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XZADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA55 |page=55 |title=Criticism Mounts Over 'Super Fly' |date=September 28, 1972 |journal=Jet |volume=43 |number=1 |issn=0021-5996 |publisher=Johnson Publishing}}</ref>\n\nBarry advocated for a larger budget for education<ref>{{cite news |title= D.C. School Board Rescinds Budget Cut of Teaching Jobs |first= Andrew |last= Barnes |date= July 20, 1972 |work= The Washington Post |page= B1 |id= {{ProQuest|148299037}} }}</ref> and raises for teachers.<ref>{{cite news |title= Rally Planned |work= The Washington Post |date= September 27, 1972 |first= Bart |last= Barnes |id= {{ProQuest|148238588}} }}</ref> Barry also supported the appointment of [[Barbara Sizemore]] as the city's superintendent, making Washington, DC the country's first major city with a woman as School Board Superintendent.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. Barbara Sizemore New D.C. School Head |first=Larry |last=Brown |date=August 11, 1973 |work=Baltimore Afro-American |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lkxGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=deUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=922,1081088&dq=marion-barry+sizemore&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Senate held up annual payments to the district because of debate over whether the federal government should continue to pay for holding the district's partisan elections, Barry called for public hearings on the matter.<ref name=automatic>{{cite news |title= Automatic U.S. Payment For City Asked By Barry |work= The Washington Post |first=Richard E. |last= Prince |date= November 10, 1972 |id= {{ProQuest|148395466}} }}</ref> He also commented, \"Since it is a known fact that the majority makeup of an elected government will be black, the conferees' agreement indicates to me that some members of Congress are saying that black people cannot be fiscally responsible, and therefore, have to have a predominantly white Congress overseeing how our monies are spent.\"<ref name=automatic />\n\n==1974\u20131979: D.C. Council and shooting==\nUpon establishment of [[District of Columbia home rule|Washington's home rule]] in 1974, Barry was elected an at-large member of Washington's first elected [[city council]]. In that position, he served as chair of the District of Columbia Committee on Finance and Revenue. He was re-elected in 1976.\n\nWhile serving on the [[Council of the District of Columbia|D.C. City Council]], Barry was shot on March 9, 1977, by radical [[1977 Washington, D.C. attack and hostage taking|Hanafi Muslims]] (a breakaway sect of the [[Nation of Islam]]) when they overran the [[John A. Wilson Building|District Building]].<ref name=just /> Barry was shot near his heart<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/shooting.htm | title=Barry 'A Very Lucky Man'; Bullet Stopped Near Heart | first=Kathy | last=Sawyer |work=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 1977}}</ref> during the two-day [[1977 Washington, D.C. attack and hostage taking|1977 Hanafi Siege]] in which hostages were held by the terrorists. This was finally defused by the FBI and Muslim ambassadors.<ref>{{cite news |title=12 Hanafi Moslems Face Indictments |agency=Associated Press |date=May 6, 1977 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3hBaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gUsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6770,784531&dq=marion+barry&hl=en}}</ref> Barry recovered from his injury.\n\n===1978 mayoral election===\n{{Main|Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1978}}\nHaving credentials as an activist, legislator, and \"hero\" in a hostage crisis, as well as an early endorsement from the ''Washington Post'',<ref name=78endors>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry for Mayor |author= editorial |work=The Washington Post |date=August 30, 1978 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/78endors.htm |access-date=November 19, 2010}}</ref> Barry was elected as mayor after [[Walter Washington]], the district's first mayor, fell out of political favor in the 1978 election.\n\nIn the Democratic primary\u2014the real contest in the heavily Democratic, black-majority city\u2014Barry ran with the campaign slogan \"Take a Stand\" and the promise to improve the \"bumbling and bungling\" Washington administration. He won the Democratic primary election against his main rivals Mayor Washington and council chairman [[Sterling Tucker]]. The vote was so close that final tally was in doubt for over two weeks.<ref name=wapo-1978-09-28>{{cite news |title=Mayor Says Barry Won D.C. Vote; Mayor Concedes Barry Victorious In District Voting |first=Paul W. |last=Valentine |work=The Washington Post |page=C1 |date=September 28, 1978 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/135572972.html?FMT=ABS |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> Barry defeated his Republican opponent [[Arthur Fletcher]] and two other minor candidates in a landslide general election in November.<ref name=wapo-1976-11-08>{{cite news |title=Barry Wins Mayor Race In a Breeze; Democrats Score Virtual Sweep to Retain Dominance Election '78/The District Barry Is Decisive Winner In Race for District Mayor |first=Milton |last=Coleman |author2=Bredemeier, Kenneth |work=The Washington Post |page=A1 |date=November 8, 1978 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/135607392.html?FMT=ABS |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> He was the second person elected to the mayor's office.\n\n==1979\u20131991: Washington, D.C. Mayor==\n===First term===\nBarry's first four years in office were characterized by increased efficiency in city administration and government services, in particular the sanitation department. Barry also instituted his signature summer jobs program, in which summer employment was made available to every school-age resident. At the same time, Barry straightened the city's chaotic finances and attacked the deficit by introducing spending controls and laying off ten percent of the city's workforce.<ref name=tenure>{{cite news|title=Barry Brings Halt to Turbulent D.C. Saga/Barry's Tenure Was A Roller-Coaster Ride|first=Vernon|last=Loeb|work=The Washington Post|date=May 22, 1998|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barryyears0522b.htm|access-date=November 19, 2010}}</ref> Each year of his first term saw a budget surplus of at least [[United States dollar|US$]]13 million.<ref name=blackent>{{cite news|title=Washington: District of Commerce|last=Jones|first= Patricia A.|work=Black Enterprise|date=June 1986|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwWMVXT0vcwC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=%22Marion+Barry%22+surplus&source=bl&ots=bkUQMNDhE_&sig=IOcT8snxc5FcgaPH4B_R-QSnSp4&hl=en&ei=-mjlTKDyMoGClAfC7NTeCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCQQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=%22Marion%20Barry%22%20surplus&f=false}}</ref> District of Columbia political reporter Jonetta Rose Barras characterized the first Barry administration as \"methodical, competent, and intellectually superior.\"<ref name=barras />\n\nHowever, unemployment rose dramatically during Barry's first administration, as did crime rates, in part because many of his layoffs were centered in the police department (1,500 terminations by 1981). His campaign promise to \"take the boards off\" public housing&nbsp;\u2013 ''i.e.'', to rehabilitate dilapidated and condemned public housing units&nbsp;\u2013 was slow in fulfillment. The city's debt was a constant problem as well: Barry had recalculated the Washington Administration's claim of a $41 million surplus and found that the city was $285 million in debt,<ref name=barras /> a long-term accrual that his annual surpluses were unable to surmount by the end of his term. Graft and embezzlement among Barry appointees, such as Employment Services director Ivanhoe Donaldson, began late in Barry's first term, although it would not be discovered for several years.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref name=1982endorse>{{cite news|title=The Next Mayor ...|work=The Washington Post|date=September 10, 1982|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/82endors.htm|access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Barry was personally touched by a number of \"mini-scandals\". He had travels with finances he often kept secret. He was first reported to be using [[cocaine]] at downtown nightclubs.<ref name=tenure />\n\n===Second term===\nIn 1982, Barry faced re-election against a challenge from fellow Democrat [[Patricia Roberts Harris]], an African-American woman who had served in two cabinet positions under President [[Jimmy Carter]], as well as from council members [[John L. Ray]] and [[Charlene Drew Jarvis]]. In the primary election held September 14, 1982, Barry won by a landslide, with over 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=429133|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor \u2013 D Primary Race \u2013 Sep 14, 1982|publisher=}}</ref> He won 82% of the vote in the November 11 general election against Republican candidate E. Brooke Lee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52605|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race|date=November 2, 1982|publisher=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\nBarry's second term was much more troublesome than his first. Though Washington experienced a massive real estate boom that helped alleviate the city's fiscal problems for a time,<ref name=making /> government spending skyrocketed; the administration posted a fifth straight budget surplus,<ref name=blackent /> but the next year struggled with a $110 million deficit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry's Chickens Prepare to Roost|first=Eric|last=Pianin|author2=Sherwood, Tom|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 19, 1983|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/84budget.htm}}</ref> Much of the disparity was caused by Barry's policy of combatting unemployment by creating government jobs; the city government's payrolls swelled so greatly that by 1986, nobody in the administration knew exactly how many employees it had.<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nWasteful contract spending also became a problem in the second Barry administration. In his first term Barry had made a point of insisting that any firm wishing to do business with the city have minority partners, and shepherding legislation requiring 35% of all contracts to go to minority-owned firms. The policy was modified in his second term such that the administration gave contracts to Barry's political connections and high-end campaign contributors to the tune of $856 million.<ref name=blackent /> The city did not exercise sufficient oversight. The cost of services such as heating oil for the public schools inflated 40 percent, without any guarantee that the goods and services were being provided. City councilman [[John A. Wilson (politician)|John A. Wilson]] commented that \"What started out to benefit the minority community at large has meant some politically influential blacks can move out to posh suburbs.\"<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nMajor scandal caught up to the mayor in his second term. Several of his associates were indicted for financial malfeasance, including former administration officials Ivanhoe Donaldson and Alphonse G. Hill. Barry began to be plagued by rumors and press reports of womanizing and of alcohol and drug abuse; in particular, stories abounded of his cocaine use in the city's nightclubs and red-light district. In 1983, Barry's ex-wife, Mary Treadwell, was convicted of fraudulently using federal funds given to Pride, Inc., a group that helped local youth find employment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Son of the soil, Barry had guts, guile on his side|work=Washington Times|first=Adrienne T.|last= Washington, DC|page=A5|date= January 19, 1990|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0EE9E70E560E7&p_docnum=12&p_queryname=24}}</ref> In 1984, Barry's one-time lover Karen Johnson was convicted of cocaine possession and contempt of court for refusing to testify to a grand jury about Barry's drug use.<ref name=timeline>{{cite news|title=The Barry Years: Triumphs and Troubles|first=Jane|last=Ashley |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 21, 1990|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/timeline.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Barry's second four years in office had some high points, including the District's entry into the open [[bond market]] with Wall Street's highest credit rating,<ref name=tenure /> and Barry's nomination speech for Jesse Jackson at the 1984 Democratic Convention.<ref name=timeline />\n\n===Third term===\nBarry sought a third term as mayor in 1986. By this time, his dominance of city politics was so absolute that he faced only token opposition in the Democratic primary in the form of former school board member Mattie Taylor, whom Barry dispatched rather easily. Barry had expected to face Jesse Jackson, who had been encouraged by colleagues to seek the mayoralty, and who had been relatively popular in stark contrast to Barry's declining reputation. Barry, who knew that most of Jackson's income came from delivering speeches, used his political clout to arbitrarily disqualify Jackson by getting a law passed that said anyone who made more than a certain amount in [[Honorarium|honoraria]] was ineligible to run for D.C. office. Council members jokingly called this the \"Jesse Jackson law,\" as it was legislated expressly to keep Jackson out of the mayoral race. As expected, Barry defeated Republican city councilwoman [[Carol Schwartz]] fairly handily in the November 4 general election. However, Schwartz managed to win 33 percent of the vote\u2014the first time a Republican had crossed the 30-percent barrier in a general election.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52604|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1986|publisher=}}</ref> For the third time, Barry received the endorsement of ''The Washington Post'' but \"with far greater reservations and misgivings\" than at any time in the past.<ref name=1986endorse>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry for Mayor |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=November 2, 1986 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/86endors.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy this time, Barry was openly suffering from the effects of longstanding addictions to cocaine and alcohol; he would later admit that he lost control of his drug habit soon after being sworn in for a third term.<ref name=dreamcity /> His public appearances were marked by his glassy eyes and slurred speech. His aides began scheduling all of his daily events later and later in the day as he was arriving to work as late as lunchtime, and nodding off to sleep at his desk. His ability to function as mayor had become so impaired that even his closest associates urged him not to run again. They tried to create an endowed professorship for him at the [[University of the District of Columbia]]. In the wake of Barry's inattention, the city declined badly. Barry was watching [[Super Bowl XXI]] in [[Pasadena, California]] when a winter blizzard struck Washington in January 1987; city crews were accused of badly mishandling the road clearing, adversely affecting local businesses.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref name=tenure />\n\nIn 1987 [[Crack cocaine|crack]] use exploded in the city,<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. Crime Prompts Request for More Officers |agency=Associated Press |date=February 20, 1989 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ez8gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XXoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6965,7011136&dq=marion-barry+homicide&hl=en}}</ref> as did territorial wars among drug dealers; in 1988 there were 369 homicides in Washington, D.C., the most ever in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Capital's Murder Toll Equals Record |agency=Associated Press |date=October 29, 1989 |location=Cape Girardeau, Missouri |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DFkfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ptgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3888,7526355&dq=marion-barry+murder+369&hl=en}}</ref> That record was broken when the next year had 434 homicides,<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. Is Murder Capital Again |agency=Associated Press |date=November 25, 1990 |location=Bend, Oregon |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CVYPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mIYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2749,704237&dq=marion-barry+murder+434&hl=en}}</ref> and it was broken again in 1990 with 474 homicides, making Washington's murder rate the highest in the nation. The Washington, D.C. government's employment and deficits grew as city services suffered; in particular, there were frequent press reports of deaths occurring because police lacked cars to get to crime scenes, and EMS services responded slowly or went to the wrong address.<ref name=barras /><ref name=dreamcity />\n\n===1990 arrest and drug conviction===\nBy late 1989, federal officials had been investigating Barry on suspicion of illegal drug possession and use; that fall, they prosecuted several of Barry's associates for cocaine use, including Charles Lewis, a native of the [[United States Virgin Islands]]. He was implicated in a drug investigation involving Barry and a room at Washington's [[Ramada|Ramada Inn]] in December 1988.\n\n[[File:Marion Barry smoking crack.gif|thumb|right|Barry captured on a surveillance camera smoking crack cocaine during a joint sting operation by the FBI and [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|D.C. Police]].]]\n\nOn January 18, 1990, Barry was arrested with a former girlfriend, Hazel Diane \"Rasheeda\" Moore, in a [[sting operation]] at [[The Westin Washington, D.C. City Center|the Vista International Hotel]] by the FBI and [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|D.C. police]] for [[crack cocaine]] use and possession.<ref>{{cite news |title= Barry Arrested on Cocaine Charges in Undercover FBI, Police Operation |work= The Washington Post |date= January 19, 1990 |page= A1 |first= Sharon |last= LaFraniere |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/barry.htm}}</ref> Moore was an FBI informant when she invited Barry to the hotel room and insisted that he smoke freebase cocaine before they had sex, while agents in another room watched on camera, waiting for Barry to accept her offer. During the videotaped arrest, Barry says of Moore, \"Bitch set me up...I shouldn't have come up here...goddamn bitch\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jurors View Videotape of Barry Drug Arrest |work= The Washington Post |date= June 29, 1990 |page= A1 |first= Tracy |last=Thompson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/video.htm}}</ref>\n\nBarry was charged with three felony counts of perjury, 10 counts of drug possession, and one misdemeanor count of conspiracy to possess cocaine, even though the cocaine belonged to the government informant. The criminal trial ended in August 1990 with a conviction for only one possession incident, which had occurred in November 1989, and an acquittal on another. The jury [[hung jury|deadlocked]] on the remaining charges. Six or seven jurors (of whom two were white and the rest black) believed that the evidence against Barry was overwhelming and that he had displayed \"arrogance\" during the trial. Against these, five black jurors were convinced that the prosecution had falsified evidence and testimony as part of a racist conspiracy against Barry, and even disputed factual findings that had not been contested in court.<ref>{{cite news |first=Elsa |last=Walsh |author2=Barton Gellman |date=August 23, 1990|title=Chasm Divided Jurors in Barry Drug Trial|work=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/jurors.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Folks |title=Mistrial; Jurors falter on 12 of 14 counts |work=Washington Times |date=August 11, 1990 |agency=LexisNexis <!-- |access-date=February 10, 2009 -->}}</ref> After scolding the jurors for not following his instructions, presiding judge [[Thomas Penfield Jackson]] declared a [[Trial#Mistrials|mistrial]] on the remaining charges.\n\nAs a result of his arrest and the ensuing trial, Barry decided in June 1990 not to seek re-election as mayor.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Oreskes |title=After Barry, Uncertainty; Mayor's Move Brings Painful Era to Close |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE5D8163CF936A25755C0A966958260 |work=The New York Times |date=June 15, 1990 |access-date=July 7, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=File |title=Probation For Marion Barry |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1DC1331F933A25750C0A9609C8B63&scp=2&sq=Marion+Barry+drug&st=nyt |work=The New York Times |date=March 10, 2006 |access-date=February 12, 2008}}</ref> After his arrest and through his trial, Barry continued as mayor. He even ran as an independent for an at-large seat on the council against 74-year-old incumbent [[Hilda Mason]].<ref name=wapo-1990-08-30>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Files Petitions for Council Race; Mayor Plans to Appear on November Ballot as Independent\n| first=Mary Ann\n| last=French\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A10\n| date=August 30, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72611853.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> Mason, a former ally who had helped Barry recuperate after the 1977 shooting, took the challenge personally, saying, \"I do feel very disappointed in my grandson Marion Barry.\"<ref name=wapo-1990-10-22>{{cite news\n| title=Council Candidate Barry Finds a Skeptical Electorate; Mayor Hopes Loyalists Stay in His Corner\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 22, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72625885.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> Mason was endorsed by a majority of the council members<ref name=wapo-1990-10-17>{{cite news\n| title=Council Majority Endorses Mason to Block Barry's Bid\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 17, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72623623.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> and by [[Jesse Jackson]], who was running for [[Shadow congressperson|shadow senator]].<ref name=wapo-1990-10-26>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Hits 'Betrayal' By Jackson\n| first=Steve\n| last=Twomey\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=D01\n| date=October 26, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72626830.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nBarry was sentenced to six months in federal prison shortly before the November election,<ref name=wapo-1990-10-27>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Sentenced to 6 Months in Prison;Judge Says Mayor Gave Aid to Drug Culture'\n| first=Michael\n| last=York\n| author2=Thompson, Tracy\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 27, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72626231.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> which he lost&nbsp;\u2013 the first and only electoral loss of his career&nbsp;\u2013 receiving 20 percent of the overall vote, but doing well among the voters of Ward 8.<ref name=wapo-1990-11-07>{{cite news\n| title=D.C. Council; Wilson Elevated to Chairman; Cropp, Mason Beat Barry\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A31\n| date=November 7, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72629101.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> His wife and son moved out of the house later that month.<ref name=wapo-1990-11-29>{{cite news\n| title=Effi Barry and Son Move Out of Home; Separation From Mayor Follows Her Hints of Shaky Marriage\n| first1=Michael\n| last1=Abramowitz\n| author2=Trescott, Jacqueline\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=November 29, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72632874.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref>\nIn October 1991, Barry surrendered himself at a [[Federal Correctional Complex, Petersburg|correctional facility]] in [[Petersburg, Virginia]]. While serving his time, Barry was accused of letting a woman perform oral sex on him in a prison waiting room,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Transferred to New Prison After Officials Confirm Sex Allegations |agency=Associated Press |date=January 11, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y3UcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dGQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3480,3988739&dq=marion-barry+prison&hl=en}}</ref> a charge Barry denied.<ref name=cambria>{{cite news |title=Sex Charges Force Barry to U.S. Prison in Cambria |agency=Associated Press |date=January 12, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zHUcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dGQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5170,4128061&dq=marion-barry+prison+loretto&hl=en}}</ref> Barry was transferred to another [[Federal Correctional Institution, Loretto|federal prison]] in [[Loretto, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=cambria /> Barry was released in April 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Released From Prison |agency=Associated Press |location=Dubuque, Iowa |date=April 23, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HWNFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K7wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3189,5209683&dq=marion-barry+prison+loretto+released&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, after [[Toronto]] mayor [[Rob Ford]] was allegedly videotaped smoking what was reported to be crack,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2013/05/17/rob_ford_crack_scandal_mayor_must_respond_councillor_says.html|title=Rob Ford crack scandal: Toronto mayor refuses to discuss specifics of video|date=May 17, 2013|work=thestar.com}}</ref> parallels were made with the similarity to the 1990 incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/05/toronto-mayor-rob-ford-marion-barry-91554.html|title=Pundits see Ford-Barry connection|work=POLITICO}}</ref> Barry denied any similarity, stating: \"Unless he was entrapped by the government, it's not similar.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= Former Washington D.C. mayor denies any parallels between himself and scandal-plagued Rob Ford |work= National Post |date= May 17, 2013 |first= Tristin |last= Hopper |url= http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/05/17/marion-barry-denies-any-parallels-between-himself-and-rob-ford/}}</ref>\n\n==1992\u20131994: Political comeback==\n===D.C. Council===\nBarry was released from prison in 1992, and two months later filed papers to run for the Ward 8 city council seat in that year's election.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Plans on Seeking Council Seat |agency=Associated Press |location=Gadsden, Alabama |date=June 21, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BMMfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=W9gEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2085,2158233&dq=marion-barry&hl=en}}</ref> Barry ran under the slogan \"He May Not Be Perfect, But He's Perfect for D.C.\" He defeated the four-term incumbent, [[Wilhelmina Rolark]], in the Democratic primary, winning 70 percent of the vote, saying he was \"not interested in being mayor\",<ref>{{cite news\n| title=Former Mayor's Victory Worries Many in Capital\n| work=The New York Times\n| date=September 17, 1992\n| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE2DE1738F934A2575AC0A964958260\n| access-date=July 30, 2008\n}}</ref> and went on to win the general election easily.\n\n===1994 mayoral election===\n{{Main|Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1994}}\nDespite his earlier statements to the contrary, observers of Barry's council victory expressed beliefs that he was laying ground for a mayoral run in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Takes Office As Supporters Cheer; Others on Council, School Board Sworn In |first=Rene |last=Sanchez |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 3, 1993 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-926624.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091036/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-926624.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Indeed, Barry fulfilled expectations when he formally announced his candidacy for mayor on May 21, 1994, and was immediately regarded as a serious challenge to the unpopular incumbent mayor, [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry to Kick Off D.C. Comeback Campaign |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times |date=May 22, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4230125.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091058/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4230125.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Despite much opposition, including an abortive effort to recall his 1992 council election,<ref>{{cite news |title=Recall Effort Launched Against Marion Barry | first=Alvin |last=Peabody |publisher=Washington Informer |date=July 20, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2252941.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106102306/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2252941.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> Barry won a three-way Democratic primary contest for mayor with 48% of the vote on September 13, pushing Kelly into last place.<ref>{{cite news |title= Barry, Smith, Thomas win in primary|first=Janice |last=Frink Brown |work=Washington Afro-American |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2268923.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091113/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2268923.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-05}}</ref> The victory, coming after Barry's videotaped crack use and conviction, shocked the nation, carrying front-page headlines in newspapers such as the ''Los Angeles Times'' and ''Boston Globe''.<ref name=barras />\n\nAn oft-repeated Barry quote came in the aftermath of his victory in the Democratic primary election, in which he counseled those voters who opposed his mayoral campaign to \"get over it.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='I'm the Best&nbsp;... for Washington'; On Day After, Barry Advises White Voters to Deal With Him |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 15, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-909572.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091203/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-909572.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThough facing a credible challenge from Republican councilmember Carol Schwartz, who received the endorsement of the ''Washington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |title=The Mayoralty Election |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=October 9, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-914953.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091149/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-914953.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Barry was victorious in the general election with 56% to Schwartz's 42% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52602|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1994|publisher=}}</ref> Not only was this easily the strongest showing by a Republican mayoral candidate since the restoration of home rule, but it was also the first time since then that a Democratic candidate for mayor had dropped below the 60 percent mark. It would not occur again until [[Muriel Bowser]] won the [[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 2014|2014 general election]] with 54% of the vote.\n\n==1995\u20131999: D.C. Mayor fourth term==\n[[File:Marion Barry, 1996 in Washington, D.C (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Barry in 1996]]\nBarry was sworn into office on January 2, 1995, and was almost immediately confronted with a financial crisis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry's Fourth Term Off to a Rocky Start |first=Howard |last=Schneider |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 16, 1995 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-816501.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091216/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-816501.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> The budgetary problems of his previous administrations had only increased during Kelly's term, with city officials estimating a fiscal 1996 deficit between $700 million and $1 billion.<ref name=barras /> In addition, city services remained extremely dysfunctional due to mismanagement. One month into his term, Barry declared that the city government was \"unworkable\" in its present state and lobbied Congress to take over the areas of its operation that were analogous to typical state government functions.<ref>[http://www.davidcatania.com/publicdocuments/DC_budget_timeline.pdf Davidcatania.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317074803/http://www.davidcatania.com/publicdocuments/DC_budget_timeline.pdf |date=March 17, 2012}}</ref> [[Wall Street]], which Barry had convinced just after his election to continue investing in municipal bonds, reduced the city's credit rating to \"junk status.\"<ref name=barras /> Instead of implementing Barry's proposals, the newly Republican Congress (who had come to power on promises of decreasing federal spending) placed several city operations into receivership and created the [[District of Columbia Financial Control Board]] to assume complete authority over the city's day-to-day spending and finances, including overrule of the mayor's fiscal decisions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Congress Creates Board to Oversee Washington, D.C. |first=Michael |last=Janofsky |newspaper=The New York Times |date=April 8, 1995 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE7DB1739F93BA35757C0A963958260}}</ref>\n\nThe next two years were dominated by budgetary and policy battles between Barry and the control board&nbsp;\u2014 along with [[Chief financial officer|Chief Financial Officer]] [[Anthony A. Williams]]&nbsp;\u2014 for power over the District of Columbia's operation. The conflict was ultimately settled when in 1997 the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton Administration]] and [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Lauch Faircloth]] agreed on legislation that rescued the city from its financial crisis but stripped Barry of all authority (including hiring and firing) over nine district agencies, making them directly answerable to the control board. Barry was left with control of only the Department of Parks and Recreation, the public libraries, and the Board of Tourism, as well as the ceremonial trappings of his office&nbsp;\u2014 a condition he characterized \"a rape of democracy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Reforms are certain to reshape life in D.C. |first=Vincent S. |last=Morris |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=July 31, 1997 |url= https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-56806634}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=DC and the Feds |publisher=National Public Radio |date=August 15, 1997 |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1038794}}</ref>\n\nBarry declined to run for a fifth term in office in June 1998, stating his belief that Congress would not restore full home rule while he was mayor.<ref>{{cite news |title=Controversial D.C. Mayor Marion Barry Says He'll Call It Quits |agency= Associated Press |work=Los Angeles Sentinel |date=June 3, 1998 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-490575141.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091400/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-490575141.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> He was succeeded by city CFO [[Anthony A. Williams]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n==2000\u20132014: D.C. Council==\n[[File:Marion Barry at 1998 St Patrick's Day Parade.jpg|thumb|Barry at the 1998 Washington, D.C. [[Saint Patrick's Day]] Parade]]\n\nAfter leaving office, Barry performed consulting work for an investment banking firm. On March 6, 2002, Barry declared his intention to challenge at-large council member [[Phil Mendelson]] in the Democratic primary.<ref name=wapo-2002-03-07>{{cite news\n| title=Barry to Heed 'Calling' With Bid for D.C. Council; Comeback Campaign Takes Aim at Mendelson\n| first=Craig\n| last=Timberg\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=B01\n| date=March 7, 2002\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/110223673.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 7, 2008\n}}</ref> Within a month, he decided against running, after an incident in which U.S. Park Police found traces of marijuana and cocaine in his car.<ref name=wapo-2002-04-05>{{cite news\n| title=Without Barry, the Plot Gets Thinner; Council Member Mendelson Loses a Key Foe, and Supporters Lose a Key Voice\n| first=Craig\n| last=Timberg\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=B04\n| date=April 5, 2002\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/112946966.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 7, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, 2004, Barry announced that he was running in the Democratic primary for the Ward 8 council seat, a position he held before becoming mayor. Barry received 58% of the vote, defeating the incumbent council member, [[Sandy Allen (D.C. Council)|Sandy Allen]], on September 14, 2004.<ref name=2004p>{{cite web |title=Certified Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=September 14, 2004 |url=http://www.dcboee.org/information/elec_2004/sep14cr/En_W8_Council.shtm |access-date=December 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314151025/http://www.dcboee.org/information/elec_2004/sep14cr/En_W8_Council.shtm |archive-date=March 14, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barry received 95% of the vote in the general election, giving him a victory in the race to represent Ward 8 in the Council.<ref name=2004g>{{cite web|title=Certified Summary Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=November 18, 2004 |url=http://www.dcboee.org/pdf_files/Summary_2.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725222439/http://www.dcboee.org/pdf_files/Summary_2.pdf |archivedate=July 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2006 mayoral election, Barry endorsed [[Adrian Fenty]] despite [[Linda W. Cropp|Linda Cropp]] hiring many members of Barry's former [[political machine]]. Barry has publicly clashed with Fenty over [[D.C. United]]'s proposed soccer stadium in Barry's Ward 8. Barry was the stadium's most outspoken supporter on the council, whereas Fenty attempted to distance himself from his initial support for the project.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Nakamura |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/12/AR2007091202445.html |title=Fenty Goes Fishing Around Poplar Point |work=The Washington Post |date=September 13, 2007 |page=B01}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, Marion Barry was chosen as one of fifty wax statues to debut in the Washington D.C. franchise of [[Madame Tussauds|Madame Tussauds Wax Museum]]. Barry was chosen by a majority of Washington residents and tourists from Tussauds' \"Top 10 Wish List,\" in a contest that pitted him against [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]], [[Al Gore]], [[Denzel Washington]], [[Carl Bernstein]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Martin Sheen]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Nancy Reagan]] and [[Oprah Winfrey]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Darragh |last=Johnson |author2=Roberts, Roxanne |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/17/AR2007071701643.html |title=Washington's Mayor for Life To Be Truly Immortalized&nbsp;\u2013\u2014in Wax |work=The Washington Post |date=July 18, 2007 |page=B01}}</ref>\n\nBarry ran for re-election in 2008 and easily held off all five challengers in the Democratic primary: Ahmad Braxton-Jones, Howard Brown, Chanda McMahan, Sandra Seegars and Charles Wilson.<ref name=dcboee-list-2008>{{cite web\n| title=List of Candidates in Ballot Order for the September 9, 2008 Congressional and Council Primary Election\n| url=http://www.dcboee.org/nws/pdf_files/pn_146.pdf\n| author=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics\n| date=July 26, 2008\n| access-date=August 1, 2008\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730181508/http://www.dcboee.org/nws/pdf_files/pn_146.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref> No Republican or [[D.C. Statehood Green Party|Statehood Green]] candidates filed to run in the Ward 8 council race.\n\n===Vote on gay marriage===\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia}}\nIn May 2009, Barry voted against a bill committing Washington, D.C. to recognize [[same-sex marriage]]s performed elsewhere. During his 2008 reelection campaign, Barry had told members of the Gertrude Stein Democratic Club, the city's largest [[LGBT]] political group, \"I don't think you should make [supporting the bill] a [[Litmus test (politics)|litmus test]]. But if a bill like that were to come up, I would vote for it.\"<ref name=june2008speech>{{cite news |last=Chibarro Jr. |first=Lou |title=Marion Barry announces support for gay marriage: D.C. Council member breaks long silence on issue |work=Washington Blade |date=June 24, 2008 |url=http://www.washblade.com/thelatest/thelatest.cfm?blog_id=19248 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20080628222745/http://www.washblade.com/thelatest/thelatest.cfm?blog_id=19248 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 28, 2008 |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> Following his May 2009 vote against recognizing gay marriages, Barry was criticized for what activists believed to be an apparent [[Flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]].<ref name=moralcompass /> Councilman [[Phil Mendelson]] said he was surprised by the vote because Barry had signed on as a co-introducer of the marriage bill.<ref name=moralcompass>{{cite news|last=Chibarro Jr. |first=Lou |title=Barry warns of racial divide over marriage: After heated debate, Council votes 12\u20131 to recognize gay unions from other states |work=[[Washington Blade]] |date=May 8, 2009 |url=https://www.washblade.com/2009/5-8/news/localnews/14495.cfm |access-date=July 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611074054/http://www.washblade.com/2009/5-8/news/localnews/14495.cfm |archivedate=June 11, 2009}}</ref> Barry said his position had not changed and warned that the council needed to move slowly on this issue. Citing his belief that the local [[African Americans|African American]] community was overwhelmingly opposed to gay marriage, \"All hell is going to break loose\", Barry said. \"We may have a civil war. The black community is just adamant against this.\"<ref name=moralcompass /><ref name=may2009vote>{{cite news |last=Craig |first=Tim |title=Barry Warns of \"Civil War\" Over Gay Marriage |work=The Washington Post |date=May 5, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/05/barry_warns_of_civil_war_over.html |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Legal problems===\n====Failures to file tax returns and pay taxes====\nOn October 28, 2005, Barry pleaded guilty to the [[misdemeanor]] charges stemming from an IRS investigation. The mandatory drug testing for the hearing showed Barry as being positive for cocaine and marijuana. On March 9, 2006, he was sentenced to three years [[probation]] for misdemeanor charges of failing to pay federal and local taxes, and underwent drug counseling.<ref>{{cite news |first=Debbi |last=Wilgoren |author2=Woodlee, Yolanda |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/09/AR2006030900848.html |title=Barry Sentenced to Three Years of Probation |work=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |author2=Leonnig, Carol D |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/10/AR2006011002018.html |title=Barry Tested Positive for Cocaine Use In the Fall |work=The Washington Post |date=January 11, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, federal prosecutors sought to have his probation revoked for failure to file his 2005 tax return. U.S. Magistrate Judge Deborah Robinson refused, saying that prosecutors had not proved that the failure was willful, even if Barry was aware he had missed the deadline.<ref name=avoids>{{cite news |title=Barry avoids prison in tax case |date=June 21, 2007 |work=The Washington Times |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/jun/21/barry-avoids-prison-in-tax-case/}}</ref> According to Judge Robinson, sentencing Barry to jail without proving that he willfully failed to file his taxes would contradict precedent set by the United States Supreme Court.<ref name=avoids />\n\n[[File:Marionbarry001.jpg|thumb|Barry in 2007]]\nOn February 9, 2009, prosecutors filed a motion in federal court to revoke Barry's probation for not filing his 2007 tax return, which violated his probation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Westley |title=Prosecutors: Jail ex-D.C. mayor Barry over taxes |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hbca1B6HG_Pll1HiP0eGOpHslkIQD968B8KG0 |agency=The Associated Press |work=Google News |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009}}</ref><ref name=wanttosend>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors Want to Send Barry to Jail |first=Will |last=Thomas |work=[[WTTG]] |publisher=Fox Television Stations, Inc. |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009 |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/020909_marion_barry_tax_issues}}</ref> According to one prosecutor, Barry has not filed his taxes eight of the last nine years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors urge jail for Marion Barry |work=UPI via COMTEX |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009 |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/prosecutors-urge-jail-marion-barry/story.aspx?guid={E3EAB21A-5E6C-497D-9C13-0223F8345832}&dist=msr_1}}</ref> Barry said the reason he did not file his taxes is because of distractions from his medical problems, although he noted that there is \"no excuse\" for not filing.<ref name=kept /> In an interview, Barry said he had been undergoing four-hour [[dialysis|dialyses]] three times a week as treatment for a problem with his kidney.<ref name=kept>{{cite news |title=Barry Says Kidney Issues Kept Him From Filing Taxes |first=Martin |last=Weil |work=Washington Post |date=February 11, 2009 |page=B04 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/10/AR2009021003625.html}}</ref><ref name=offers>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Offers Excuse For Not Filing Tax Return |first=Brian |last=Johnson |work=[[WUSA-TV]] |date=February 11, 2009 |url=http://www.wusa9.com/rss/local_article.aspx?storyid=81365 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235246/http://www.wusa9.com/rss/local_article.aspx?storyid=81365 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=offers /> At that point, a kidney donor had been identified, but the operation had yet to be scheduled.<ref name=offers /> On February 17, [[WTOP-FM]] reported that, according to Barry's attorney, Barry had filed his federal and District tax returns for 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Better late than never? Barry files 2007 taxes |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |date=February 17, 2009 |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=25&sid=1604045}}</ref> The same day, Barry was admitted to Howard University Hospital to prepare for a kidney transplant the next day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry to Get Kidney Transplant |last=Stewart |first=Nikita; Harris, Hamil R |work=The Washington Post |date=February 19, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/02/report_barry_to_get_kidney_tra.html}}</ref> Barry was released from the hospital on February 27,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry released from hospital |date=February 28, 2009 |work=Washington Times |url=http://washingtontimes.com/news/2009/feb/28/metro-briefs-95126010/}}</ref> but he was readmitted on March 2 due to large amounts of air in his abdominal cavity and also due to Barry's complaints of serious pains,<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Back In Hospital |first=Karen |last=GreyHouston |work=[[WTTG]] |publisher=Fox Television Stations, Inc. |date=March 4, 2009 |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/local/030409_barry_back_in_hospital}}</ref> both of which were caused by the combination of medications Barry was taking after the operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry back in hospital, doing well |first=Elizabeth |last=Hillgrove |work=The Washington Times |date=March 5, 2009 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/05/barry-back-in-hospital-doing-well/}}</ref> Barry was released from the hospital on March 6.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Goes Home from Hospital |first=Matt |last=Ackland |date=March 6, 2009 |work=[[WTTG]] |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/030609_marion_barry_released}}</ref> On April 17, 2009, the prosecution withdrew their request to revoke Barry's probation.<ref>{{cite news |title=CURL: Barry holds court on D.C. streets |date=April 17, 2009 |work=Washington Times |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/17/marion-barry-holds-court-on-the-streets-of-distric/}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2011, the Internal Revenue Service filed a notice of federal tax lien against Barry because of $3,200 of unpaid federal income taxes for 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=IRS files tax lien of more than $3,200 against Barry |first=Jim |last=McElhatton |work=The Washington Times |date=December 14, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/14/irs-files-tax-lien-against-barry-for-more-than-320/}}</ref> Barry attributed the lien to poor communication between the Internal Revenue Service and his representatives.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry: New tax lien a result of poor communication |first=Tom |last=Howell Jr |work=The Washington Times |date=December 15, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/15/barry-new-tax-lien-result-poor-communication/}}</ref>\n\n====Alleged traffic violations====\nOn September 10, 2006, Barry was stopped by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] Uniformed Division police officers after stopping at a green light and running a red light.<ref name=tickets>{{cite news |title=Secret Service Tickets Barry |last=Woodlee |first=Yolanda; Lengel, Allan |work=The Washington Post |date=September 11, 2006 |page=B08 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/10/AR2006091001028.html}}</ref><ref name=testifies>{{cite news |title=Secret Service Testifies Against Barry |first=Brett |last=Zongker |agency=The Associated Press |work=The Washington Post |date=June 12, 2007 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/12/AR2007061202438_pf.html}}</ref> According to a Secret Service spokesman, the police officers pulled over his car, smelled alcohol, and administered a [[Driving under the influence#Field sobriety testing|field sobriety test]].<ref name=tickets /> Barry was then taken to the U.S. Capitol Police station for a [[breathalyzer]] test.<ref name=tickets /> The Secret Service said that the breathalyzer test did not give an accurate reading, but Barry later said that it gave a successful reading of 0.02%, which is less than the legal limit of 0.08%.<ref name=tickets /> The police officers asked Barry to give a urine analysis, which Barry refused.<ref name=tickets /> The officers gave Barry a ticket for running a red light and failing to submit to a urine analysis.<ref name=tickets /> He was also charged with driving an unregistered vehicle and misuse of temporary tags.<ref name=former>{{cite news |title=Former D.C. Mayor Marion Barry Acquitted on Drunk Driving, Related Charges |work=Fox News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 13, 2007 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,282034,00.html |access-date=June 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616164658/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,282034,00.html |archive-date=June 16, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barry pleaded not guilty to the charges.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Pleads Not Guilty to DUI |first=Henri E. |last=Cauvin |work=The Washington Post |date=November 15, 2006 |page=B04 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/14/AR2006111400652_pf.html}}</ref> Prosecutors offered Barry a deal to drop the charge of driving under the influence in exchange for a guilty plea from Barry; he declined.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Rejects Offer, Maintains Innocence |first=Henri E. |last=Cauvin |work=The Washington Post |date=February 3, 2007|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/02/AR2007020200834.html}}</ref> A judge found him not guilty of the charges.<ref name=former />\n\nOn December 16, 2006, the [[United States Park Police|Park Police]] pulled over Barry for driving too slowly, which Barry later said was because he was trying to figure out where to enter an elementary school's parking lot for a nonprofit foundation's event.<ref name=delayed>{{cite news |title=Barry Says Park Police Delayed Him for 3 Hours |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |work=The Washington Post |date=December 19, 2006 |page=B06 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/18/AR2006121801223_pf.html}}</ref> After looking up Barry's record, the police officer told Barry that his license had been suspended and ticketed Barry for operating a vehicle on a suspended license, despite Barry's insistence to the contrary.<ref name=delayed /> Two days later, the D.C. Department of Motor Vehicles confirmed that Barry's license had not actually been suspended and said a computer glitch must have caused the error.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former D.C. Mayor Barry Alleges Improper Traffic Stop |work=Fox News |agency=Associated Press |date=December 19, 2006 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,237384,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613040415/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C237384%2C00.html |archivedate=June 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2014, Barry was in a traffic accident in the district, which his spokesperson blamed on a \"hypoglycemic attack\" due to his [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]]. At the time of the accident Barry had $2,800 in unpaid tickets for speeding and parking violations accumulated since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeBonis|first1=Mike|title=Marion Barry racked up $2,800 in unpaid tickets before Saturday night crash|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/marion-barry-racked-up-2800-in-unpaid-tickets-before-saturday-night-crash/2014/08/04/cd5ffed2-1c18-11e4-ae54-0cfe1f974f8a_story.html|website=www.washingtonpost.com|publisher=The Washington Post|access-date=August 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Conflict of interest: personal benefit from contract to girlfriend====\nOn July 4, 2009, Barry was taken into custody by the Park Police after political consultant Donna Watts-Brighthaupt, his ex-girlfriend, claimed he was [[stalking]] her.<ref name=july2009wapo>{{cite news |author=Tim Johnson |author2=Jenna Johnson |title=The Charge Against Barry: Stalking His Ex-Girlfriend |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 6, 2009 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/05/AR2009070501056.html |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> Barry was arrested and charged with \"[[misdemeanor]] stalking\". Following an interview with authorities, he was released on citation and told he must appear before the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]] on July 9.<ref name=july2009arrest>{{cite news |title=D.C.'s Marion Barry arrested again |work=[[CNN]] |date=July 5, 2009 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/07/05/marion.barry.arrested/ |access-date=July 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name=july2009nyt>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Charged With Stalking a Woman |work=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 5, 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/06/us/06barry.html?ref=global-home |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> However, all charges were dropped on July 8.<ref name=chargesdropped>{{cite news |title=Stalking charges against Barry dropped |publisher=[[WTOP-FM|WTOP]] |date=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=25&sid=1713945 |access-date=July 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn investigative report by a special counsel said that Barry had personally benefited from a contract that he had awarded to his then-girlfriend Donna Watts-Brighthaupt.<ref name=bennett>{{cite news |title=Bennett report: Barry benefited from city contract obtained for ex-girlfriend |work=The Washington Post |first=Tim |last=Craig |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2010/02/bennett_report_barry_benefited.html?wpisrc=nl_buzz}}</ref><ref name=report>{{cite news |title=Report of Investigation Pursuant to D.C. Council Resolution 18\u2013217 |work=Robert S. Bennett, Hogan & Hartson LLP, via The Washington Post |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/bennettReport%20of%20Investigation%20Pursuant%20to%20DC%20Council%20Resolution%2018-217.pdf}}</ref> The report stated that Barry had awarded a contract to Watts-Brighthaupt, who then repaid money owed to Barry with the proceeds of the contract.<ref name=bennett /> When interviewed by the special counsel, Watts-Brighthaupt admitted to plagiarizing substantial portions of her study from a publicly available study by the United States Department of Education.<ref name=report /> The special counsel report also said that Barry had requested 41 [[earmark (politics)|earmarks]] in 2009 worth $8.4 million, some of which were paid to organizations \"rife with waste and abuse.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Report May Put Barry in Hot Water&nbsp;\u2013 Again |work=[[WRC-TV]] |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NBC |first=Tom |last=Sherwood |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Report-Puts-Barry-in-Hot-Water-84480352.html}}</ref> The report also said that Barry had impeded the investigation by refusing to respond to questions and by telling witnesses not to respond to questions and not give subpoenaed documents to the special counsel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Barry violated city contract law |work=The Washington Times |date=February 16, 2010 |first=Joseph |last=Weber |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/feb/16/report-barry-violated-city-contract-law/?feat=home_top5_read}}</ref>\n\nBarry responded to the special counsel report by claiming he had violated no written rules or procedures on such contracts<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Ex-mayor violated laws |work=The Washington Times |date=February 17, 2010 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/feb/17/american-scene-94738815/}}</ref> and that there was no conflict of interest.<ref name=girlfriend>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry apologizes for contract to girlfriend |agency=Associated Press |work=The Washington Post |date=February 23, 2010 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/23/AR2010022303808.html}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> Barry apologized for his \"very, very poor judgment.\"<ref name=girlfriend />\n\nIn response to the special counsel's report, several council members said they would like to hear a response from Barry before considering a [[censure]]. On March 2, 2010, the Council of the District of Columbia voted 12\u20130 in favor of stripping Barry of all committee assignments, ending his chair of the Committee on Housing and Workforce Development, and removing him from the Committee on Finance and Revenue.<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. might censure Marion Barry over alleged corruption |first=Tim |last=Craig |work=The Washington Post |date=February 18, 2010 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/17/AR2010021704770.html}}</ref>\n\n===Asian American racist remarks controversy===\nAt a party celebrating his primary victory for his D.C. council seat on April 3, 2012, Barry said, \"We've got to do something about these Asians coming in, opening up businesses, those dirty shops. They ought to go, I'll just say that right now, you know. But we need African-American businesspeople to be able to take their places, too.\"<ref name=\"Asian Businesses Ought to Go\">{{cite news|last=DeBonis|first=Mike|title=UPDATE: Marion Barry apologizes for anti-Asian remarks|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/mike-debonis/post/marion-barry-stands-by-remark-that-asian-businesses-ought-to-go-from-ward-8/2012/04/05/gIQAP2TlxS_blog.html?hpid=z2|access-date=April 5, 2012|work=The Washington Post|date=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other council members, Mayor [[Vincent C. Gray|Vincent Gray]], and Delegate [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] criticized Barry's comments.<ref name= deplorable>{{cite news |title=Outcry Over Barry's 'Deplorable' Comments Is Quick and Harsh |work= The Washington Times |date=April 5, 2012 |first=Tom |last= Howell Jr. |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/apr/5/outcry-over-barrys-deplorable-comments-is-quick-an/?page=all}}</ref> Five Asian American members of the Maryland General Assembly also called on Barry to apologize in a statement, saying, \"At best, Mr. Barry's attack on Asian Americans is deeply troubling, and at worst it is race baiting.\"<ref name=wtop2012>{{cite news |title=Barry Apologizes for Disparaging Comments About Asians |date=April 5, 2012 |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=41&sid=2816672}}</ref>\n\nBarry apologized for his comments, saying in a written statement, \"It is to these less than stellar Asian-American businessmen in Ward 8 that my remarks were directed, not the whole of Asian businessmen in Ward 8 or the Asian-American population.\"<ref name= deplorable />\n\nWhile apologizing to Asian Americans, Barry used the anti-Polish slur [[Polack]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-05-24/local/35457530_1_marion-barry-asian-community-asian-american | work=The Washington Post | first=Paul | last=Schwartzman | title=Marion Barry commits new gaffe while apologizing to Asians | date=June 20, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123140441/http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-05-24/local/35457530_1_marion-barry-asian-community-asian-american | archivedate=January 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarry married Effi Slaughter, his third wife, just after announcing his candidacy for mayor in 1978. The couple had one son, [[Marion Christopher Barry]], who died of a drug overdose on August 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry's son scheduled to be sentenced in drug case |first=Maggie |last=Fazeli Fard |date= September 27, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/crime-scene/post/marion-barrys-son-to-be-sentenced-in-drug-case/2011/09/27/gIQA8eDQ1K_blog.html}}</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=barry&GSfn=marion+&GSmn=christopher&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSob=n&GRid=173370805&df=all& Marion Christopher Barry, memorial; findagrave.com] Retrieved May 21, 2017</ref> The Barrys separated in November 1990, soon after he was caught on videotape smoking crack cocaine with an ex-model and propositioning her for sex.<ref>{{cite news |title=Effi Barry and Son Move Out of Home; Separation From Mayor Follows Her Hints of Shaky Marriage |last1= Abramowitz |first1= Michael |last2= Trescott |first2= Jacqueline |work= The Washington Post |date= November 29, 1990 |page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Barry's ex-wife, 63, dies of leukemia: Praised for public-health work |work= The Washington Times |date= September 7, 2007 |page= B1 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=11B86DF574909AA0&p_docnum=5&p_queryname=29}}</ref> They divorced in 1993, but she returned to Washington and supported him in his successful bid for a city council seat in 2004. Effi died on September 6, 2007, after an 18-month battle with [[acute myeloid leukemia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Effi Barry to Lie in Repose at Wilson Building |first=Nikita |last=Stewart |work=The Washington Post |date=September 8, 2007 |page=B02 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/07/AR2007090701833_pf.html}}</ref>\n\nBarry married Cora Masters on January 8, 1993.<ref name= towed>{{cite news |title= Barry to Wed |work= The Cincinnati Post |date= December 14, 1993 |page= 14A |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0312B2FD03223&p_docnum=23&p_queryname=34}}</ref> Masters was a political science professor at the [[University of the District of Columbia]]<ref name= towed /> and his former spokeswoman.<ref>{{cite news |title= A matter of perks: Foes hit Barry for using official car in his campaigning |work= The Washington Times |date= October 25, 1990 |first= Pam |last= McClintock |page= B1 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0EEFBCE6ABA1D&p_docnum=1&p_queryname=35}}</ref> Barry's mother, Mattie Cummings, died at age 92 in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] on November 8, 2009.<ref name=cummings>{{cite news |title=Mattie Cummings, 92; mother of D.C. Council's Marion Barry |first=Adam |last=Bernstein |date=November 11, 2009 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/10/AR2009111018651.html}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Mayor Marion Barry's Memorial at Congressional Cemetery.jpg|thumb|Barry's memorial at [[Congressional Cemetery]]]]\nBarry died at United Medical Center in Washington, D.C., on November 23, 2014, from [[cardiac arrest]], aged 78.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wusa9.com/story/news/local/dc/2014/11/23/marion-barry-dies-78-years-old/19437553/|title=Marion Barry dies at 78|publisher=WUSA9.com|access-date=November 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127155320/http://www.wusa9.com/story/news/local/dc/2014/11/23/marion-barry-dies-78-years-old/19437553/|archive-date=November 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|author1=David Stout|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0|access-date=November 27, 2014|work=NY Times|publisher=NYT|date=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj>{{cite news|first1=Rebecca |last1=Ballhaus |first2=Stephen |last2=Miller|title=Marion Barry, Former Washington Mayor, Dies at 78|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/former-washington-mayor-marion-barry-dies-at-78-1416730815|access-date=November 27, 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Co|date=November 24, 2014}}</ref> Following three days of memorial observances, he was buried December 6 at Washington's [[Congressional Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mike DeBonis|title=Marion Barry's final farewell draws thousands, stretches for hours|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/marion-barrys-final-farewell-draws-thousands-stretches-for-hours/2014/12/06/41b8fd24-7b00-11e4-84d4-7c896b90abdc_story.html?tid=ptv_rellink|access-date=December 8, 2014|work=Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post|date=December 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA private monument to Barry was erected over his grave and unveiled on November 22, 2016. The event was attended by current and former D.C. Council members, former mayor Sharon Pratt Kelly, and about 150 other dignitaries, family members, and friends of Barry. The memorial, conceived and largely designed by Cora Masters Barry and Marion Christopher Barry, was carved by nationally prominent sculptor and engraver Andy Del Gallo and manufactured by Eastern Memorials (a D.C.-based funerary monument company).<ref>{{cite news|last=Jamison|first=Petr|title=Capturing Marion Barry's complicated legacy in black granite|work=The Washington Post|date=November 23, 2016|access-date=November 24, 2016|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/capturing-marion-barrys-complicated-legacy-in-black-granite/2016/11/23/5562f4ec-b032-11e6-be1c-8cec35b1ad25_story.html}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn June 2009, a documentary of Barry's life was released at Silverdocs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/17/AR2009061703642.html|title=HBO Documentary 'The Nine Lives of Marion Barry' Will Be Featured at Silverdocs|last=Fisher|first=Marc|date=June 18, 2009|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=March 22, 2016}}</ref> The HBO Documentary was released on August 2009, on HBO.\n\nIn the midst of a [[Newark mayoral election, 2014|contentious mayoral race]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]] in May 2014, [[Rutgers University]] professor and Newark city historian Clement A. Price cited Barry and [[Jackson, Mississippi]]'s [[Chokwe Lumumba]] as his role models as mayor. The citation came in an April 2014 public discussion. Professor Price had not taken sides in the 2014 contest.<ref>Zernike, Kate, [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/09/nyregion/newark-mayoral-race-seen-as-referendum-on-booker.html \"Newark Mayoral Race Seen as Referendum on Booker\"], New York ''Times'', May 8, 2014. Retrieved May 11, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Marion Barry}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[List of Alpha Phi Alpha brothers]]\n* [[List of Eagle Scouts]]\n* [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[List of members of the Council of the District of Columbia]]\n* ''[[The Nine Lives of Marion Barry]]''\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |last=Dolan |first=Michael |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/5546/visible-man |title= Visible Man: Can Marion Barry survive salvation? |work=[[Washington City Paper]] |date=January 6, 1995 |access-date=March 16, 2017}}\n*{{cite news |last=Marchenese |first=Kira |last2=Segan |first2=Sascha |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barry.htm |title=Marion Barry: Making of a Mayor |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 21, 1998 |access-date=November 23, 2014}}\n*{{cite journal |title=Marion Barry: some notes |journal=The Progressive Review |last=Smith |first=Sam |year=1998 <!-- |access-date=August 2, 2008 -->}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.dcwatch.com/mayor/980521.htm |title=The Barry Years: 40 Years of Committed Public Service |work=DCWatch |date=May 21, 1998 |access-date=November 23, 2014}}\n*Barry, Marion, and Omar Tyree. ''Mayor For Life : The Incredible Story of Marion Barry, Jr''. New York: Strebor Books, 2014. Print.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160321222301/http://theinfluence.org/sensationalism-and-hypocrisy-the-four-stages-of-every-political-drug-scandal/ The Influence \u2013 The Four Stages of Every Political Drug Scandal]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://snccdigital.org/people/marion-barry/ SNCC Digital Gateway: Marion Barry], Documentary website created by the SNCC Legacy Project and Duke University, telling the story of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee & grassroots organizing from the inside-out\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217154552/http://www.dccouncil.us/council/marion-barry District of Columbia Council Member Marion Barry] \u2013 official site\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19980129001535/http://ci.washington.dc.us/MAYOR/mayorbio.htm |date=January 29, 1998 |title=Biography of Mayor Marion Barry}}&nbsp;\u2013 District of Columbia\n* {{C-SPAN|Marion Barry}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-dc}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />for the At-Large district|years=1975\u20131979}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John L. Ray|John Ray]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Wilhelmina Rolark]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />for [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]]|years=1993\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Eydie Whittington]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sandy Allen (D.C. Council)|Sandy Allen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />for [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]]|years=2005\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[LaRuby May]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Walter Washington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]|years=[[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1978|1978]], [[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1982|1982]], [[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1986|1986]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]|years=[[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1994|1994]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Walter Washington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]|years=1979\u20131991}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]|years=1995\u20131999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Leaders of the District of Columbia}}\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n{{SNCC chairmen|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barry, Marion}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:African-American mayors]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Washington, D.C. politics]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:American shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Congressional Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Eagle Scouts]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Members of the Council of the District of Columbia]]\n[[Category:Members of the District of Columbia Board of Education]]\n[[Category:People from Itta Bena, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Democrats]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. government officials]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the former mayor of Washington, D.C|his son|Marion Christopher Barry|the former U.S. House member|Robert Marion Berry|the fruit grown in Oregon|Marionberry}}\n{{short description|20th and 21s-century American politician and former mayor of Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Marion Barry\n|image        = Crop of Marion Barry Vincent Gray.jpg{{!}}border\n|office       = 2nd and 4th [[Mayor of the District of Columbia]]\n|term_start   = January 2, 1995\n|term_end     = January 2, 1999\n|predecessor  = [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]\n|successor    = [[Anthony A. Williams|Anthony Williams]]\n|term_start1  = January 2, 1979\n|term_end1    = January 2, 1991\n|predecessor1 = [[Walter Washington]]\n|successor1   = [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]]\n|office2      = Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />from [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]]\n|term_start2  = January 2, 2005\n|term_end2    = November 23, 2014\n|predecessor2 = [[Sandy Allen (D.C. Council)|Sandy Allen]]\n|successor2   = [[LaRuby May]]\n|term_start3  = January 2, 1993\n|term_end3    = January 2, 1995\n|predecessor3 = [[Wilhelmina Rolark]]\n|successor3   = [[Eydie Whittington]]\n|office4      = Member of the [[Council of the District of Columbia]]<br />At-Large\n|term_start4  = January 2, 1975\n|term_end4    = January 2, 1979\n|predecessor4 = Position established\n|successor4   = [[John L. Ray|John Ray]]\n|office5      = Chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]]\n|term_start5  = 1960\n|term_end5    = 1961\n|predecessor5 = Position established\n|successor5   = [[Charles McDew]]\n|birth_name   = Marion Barry Jr.\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1936|03|6}}\n|birth_place  = [[Itta Bena, Mississippi]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|2014|11|23|1936|03|6}}\n|death_place  = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n|restingplace = [[Congressional Cemetery]]\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Blantie Evans (1962\u20131964)<br />Mary Treadwell (1972\u20131977)<br />Effi Slaughter (1978\u20131993)<br />Cora Masters (1993\u20132014)\n|children     = [[Marion Christopher Barry|Marion]] (with Slaughter)\n|education    = [[LeMoyne\u2013Owen College|LeMoyne-Owen College]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br />[[Fisk University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])<br />[[University of Kansas|University of Kansas, Lawrence]]<br />[[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee, Knoxville]]\n}}\n'''Marion Shepilov Barry''' (born '''Marion Barry Jr.'''; March 6, 1936&nbsp;\u2013 November 23, 2014)<ref name=nytimesobit>{{cite news|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78 |first= David|last=Stout|date=November 23, 2014|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0}}</ref> was an American politician who served as the second [[mayor of the District of Columbia]] from 1979 to 1991, and again as the fourth mayor from 1995 to 1999. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], Barry had served three tenures on the [[Council of the District of Columbia]], representing as an at-large member from 1975 to 1979 and in [[Neighborhoods in Washington, D.C.#Ward 8|Ward 8]] from 1993 to 1995, and again from 2005 to 2014. In the 1960s he was involved in the [[civil rights movement]], first as a member of the [[Nashville Student Movement]] and then serving as the first chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] (SNCC).\n\nBarry came to national prominence as mayor of the national capital, the first prominent civil rights activist to become chief executive of a major American city.<ref name=barras>{{cite book |title=The Last of the Black Emperors: The Hollow Comeback of Marion Barry in a New Age of Black Leaders |last=Barras |first=Jonetta Rose |year=1998 |publisher=Bancroft Press |isbn=0-9631246-6-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/lastofblackemper00barr }}</ref> He gave the presidential nomination speech for [[Jesse Jackson]] at the [[1984 Democratic National Convention]]. His celebrity was transformed into international notoriety in January 1990, when he was videotaped during a sting operation smoking [[crack cocaine]] and was arrested by [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) officials on [[Federal drug policy of the United States|drug charges]]. The arrest and subsequent trial precluded Barry from seeking re-election, and he served six months in a [[List of United States federal prisons|federal prison]]. After his release, he was elected to the Council of the District of Columbia in 1992. He was elected again as mayor in 1994, serving from 1995 to 1999.\n\nDespite his history of political and legal controversies, Barry was a popular and influential figure in [[Washington, D.C.]] The [[Alternative newspaper|alternative weekly]] ''[[Washington City Paper]]'' nicknamed him \"Mayor for life\", a designation that remained long after Barry left the mayoralty.<ref name=dreamcity>{{cite book |title=Dream City: Race, Power, and the Decline of Washington, D.C. |last=Jaffe |first=Harry S. |author2=Tom Sherwood |year=1994 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |isbn=0-671-76846-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/dreamcityracepow00jaff }}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' once stated that \"to understand the District of Columbia, one must understand Marion Barry\".<ref name=making>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry: Making of a Mayor. |newspaper=Washington Post |date=May 21, 1998 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barry.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==1936\u20131954: Early life==\nMarion Barry was born in rural [[Itta Bena, Mississippi]], the third child of Mattie Cummings and Marion Barry.<ref name=comeback>{{cite news |title=The 1994 Campaign: The Comeback Man in the News: From Disgrace to 'Amazing Grace': Marion Shepilov Barry Jr. |work=The New York Times |date=September 14, 1994 |first=Michael |last=Janofsky |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D02E3DC153BF937A2575AC0A962958260}}</ref><ref name=just>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Just Wants to Be Loved |first=Arthur S. |last=Brisbane |date=April 26, 1987 |page=W20 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/87prof.htm}}</ref><ref name=cummings /> His father died when he was four years old, and a year later his mother moved the family to [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=just /> where her employment prospects were better.<ref name=cummings /> His mother married David Cummings, a butcher, and together they raised eight children.<ref name= nytimesobit /> Growing up on Latham Street near [[Memphis Parkway System|South Parkway]], Marion Barry attended Florida Elementary and graduated from [[Booker T. Washington High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Booker T. Washington High]].\n\nThe first time Barry noticed racial issues was when he had to walk to school while the white students were assigned a school bus to ride. The schools were segregated, as were public facilities.<ref name=oralhistory /> He had a number of jobs as a child, including picking cotton, delivering and selling newspapers, and bagging groceries.<ref name=just /> While in high school, Barry worked as a waiter at the [[American Legion]] post and, at age 17,<ref>January 11, 1954 \u2013 Troop 184 of the [[Chickasaw Council]] (#558)</ref> earned the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]].<ref name=just /><ref name=activist>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry: The Activist Denies He's Changed |first=Milton |last=Coleman |work=Washington Post |date=January 2, 1979 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/79change.htm}}</ref>\n\nMarion Barry first began his spirit of civil rights activism when he was a paperboy in Memphis. The paper he worked for organized a contest in which any boys who gained 15 new customers could win a trip to New Orleans. Barry and a couple of the other black paperboys reached the quota of 15 new customers yet were not allowed to go on the trip to New Orleans, a segregated city. The paper said it could not afford to hire two buses to satisfy Mississippi's segregation rules. Barry decided to boycott his paper route until they agreed to send the black paperboys on a trip. After the paper offered the black paperboys a chance to go to [[St. Louis, Missouri]] on a trip, because it was not a segregated city, Barry resumed his paper route.<ref name=oralhistory>{{cite news |title=Telling Their Stories: Oral History Archives Project |date=March 21, 2011 |url=http://www.tellingstories.org/mccomb/fullmovies/marion-barry/index.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104165855/http://www.tellingstories.org/mccomb/fullmovies/marion-barry/index.html |archivedate=November 4, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==1955\u20131970: Education and civil rights activism==\n===Undergraduate studies at LeMoyne College ===\nBarry attended [[LeMoyne\u2013Owen College]], in Memphis, graduating in 1958.<ref name=comeback /> In his junior year, the racial injustices he had seen started to come together. He and his friends went to a segregated fairground in Memphis, and went at a time reserved for whites, because they wanted to see the science exhibit. When they were close to the exhibit, a policeman stopped them and asked them to leave. Barry and his friends left without protest. At that time, Barry did not know much about his race, or why they were treated poorly, but he resented the incident. Barry became more active in the [[NAACP]] chapter at LeMoyne-Owens, serving as president.<ref name=blackleaders>Rose, Thomas \"Black Leaders: Then and Now; A Personal History of Students who Led the Civil Rights Movement in the 1960s\u2014And What Happened to Them\" p. 47-52</ref> It is sometimes said that his ardent support of the civil rights movement earned him the nickname \"Shep\", in reference to Soviet politician [[Dmitri Shepilov]], and then Barry began using Shepilov as his middle name.<ref name=comeback /> But Barry stated in his autobiography that he chose the name with regard to his middle initial S, which had initially stood for nothing,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78|last=Stout|first=David|date=November 23, 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=November 21, 2016}}</ref> after having found Shepilov's name in newspapers: \"I had picked out \"Shepilov\" as a middle name because it was the only one that I knew and liked\".<ref>Barry, Marion, and Omar Tyree. ''Mayor For Life : The Incredible Story of Marion Barry, Jr''. New York: Strebor Books, 2014. P. 36</ref>\n\nIn 1958, at LeMoyne-Owens, he criticized a college trustee for remarks he felt were demeaning to African Americans, for which he was nearly expelled.<ref name=just /> While a senior and the president of the NAACP chapter, Barry heard of Walter Chandler\u2014the only white member on LeMoyne-Owen's board of trustees\u2014making comments that black people should be treated as a \"younger brother not as an adult\". Barry wrote a letter to LeMoyne's president objecting to the comments and asking if Walter Chandler could be removed from the board.<ref name=demdestiny>Walters, Ronald \"Democratic Destiny and The District of Columbia\" p. 61-69</ref> A friend of Barry's was the editor of the school newspaper, the ''Magician'', and told Barry to run the letter in the paper. From there, the letter made it to the front page of Memphis' conservative morning paper.<ref name=oralhistory />\n\n===Master's degree, Nashville Student Movement, SNCC===\n{{Alpha Phi Alpha articles}}\nBarry earned an M.S. in [[organic chemistry]] from [[Fisk University]]<ref name=comeback /> in 1960. He was a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity.<ref name=alphaconvention>{{cite news |title= Alpha's National Convention in D.C. |work= The Baltimore Afro-American |date= August 18, 1979 |page= 12 |id= {{ProQuest|532444541}} }}</ref> While in graduate school at Fisk, Barry was arrested several times while participating in the [[Nashville sit-ins]] to desegregate lunch counters and other Civil Rights Movement events.<ref name=blackleaders /> After graduating from Fisk, Barry continued to work in the Civil Rights Movement, focusing on the elimination of the [[racial segregation]] of bus passengers.\n\nIn 1960, Barry was elected as the first chairman of the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] (SNCC). He helped develop an organizing project in [[McComb, Mississippi]]. The project was both a voter registration and a direct action endeavor. Barry said he and other activists lived with the local people in order to stay safe, as well as to learn what it was like to live there. They could use that information to organize the members of the SNCC accordingly.<ref name=oralhistory />\n\n===Doctoral studies===\nBarry began doctoral studies at the [[University of Kansas]], but soon quit the program.<ref name=just /> He contemplated law school to help with his activism, but decided against it, because the delayed admission would mean that he would have to take a year off from school. Had he taken a year off, there was a chance of his being drafted into the military, and he did not want to be drafted.\n\nHe decided to go to the University of Tennessee where he was awarded a graduate fellowship. Despite being located in the South, the University of Tennessee was an integrated educational institution, a new experience for Barry.<ref name=blackleaders /> He began doctoral [[chemistry]] studies at the [[University of Tennessee]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]], the only African American in the program.<ref name=just /> He learned that he was prohibited from tutoring white children, and his wife Blantie Evans was not allowed to work at the white school.<ref name=just /> He quit the program in favor of his new duties at SNCC.\n\nIn the Spring of 1964, he attended a conference in Nashville and became one of the founders of the Southern Student Organizing Committee (SSOC).\n\n===Working for SNCC===\nAs head of SNCC, Barry led protests against racial segregation and discrimination.<ref name=just /><ref>{{cite news |title= Chicago |work= The Washington Post |date= June 26, 1964 |page= A10 |agency=Associated Press |id= {{ProQuest|142223020}} }}</ref> After he left McComb, Barry's lobbied the state legislatures to try to convince them to vote to make the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] (MFDP) the recognized Democratic party of Mississippi in the [[1964 Democratic National Convention]]. In a protest of their continuing disenfranchisement, African Americans had organized this party to prove that blacks wanted to vote and conducted a trial election. Barry slept on the boardwalk in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]] the night after speaking to the [[New Jersey Legislature]].<ref name=oralhistory />\n\nAfter he left the New York legislature, [[James Forman]] asked Barry to go to Washington, D.C. to manage SNCC's office. At the time, over half of the population of Washington D.C. was black, and they had no political representation in Congress, as the capital was considered a different kind of jurisdiction.<ref name=demdestiny />\n\nIn 1965, Barry and Evans<ref>{{cite news |title= Marion Barry |work= The Times |location= London, England |date= November 24, 2014 |page= 42 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=151CD80535948D80&p_docnum=1&p_queryname=21}}</ref> moved to Washington, D.C., to open a local chapter of SNCC. He was deeply involved in coordinating peaceful street demonstrations as well as a boycott to protest bus fare increases. Barry organized rides to work for those who needed them. The boycott cost the bus line thousands of dollars, and Barry proved his ability to organize.<ref name=activist /><ref name=blackleaders /><ref>{{cite news |title=SNCC May Call Bus Boycott |work=Baltimore Afro-American |date=January 1, 1966 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=aOhfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AAMGAAAAIBAJ&pg=5641,38921&dq=marion-barry&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nHe also served as the leader of the Free D.C. Movement, strongly supporting increased [[District of Columbia home rule|home rule]], as a Congressional committee exercised administrative rule over the district.<ref name=activist /><ref name=frustrating>{{cite news |title=Barry Finds Home Rule a Frustrating Battle |first=Dan |last=Morgan |work=The Washington Post|date=July 25, 1966 |page=B1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A47599-2004Jul13.html}}</ref> Barry quit SNCC in 1967, when [[H. Rap Brown]] became chairman of the group.<ref name=activist /> In 1967, Barry and Mary Treadwell co-founded Pride, Inc., a Department of Labor-funded program to provide job training to unemployed black men.<ref name=just /><ref name=prepareforwork>{{cite news |title= 600 Pride, Inc., Volunteers Prepare for Work |first= Hollie I. |last= West |work= The Washington Post |date= August 6, 1967 |page= C2 |id= {{ProQuest|143061918}} }}</ref> The group employed hundreds of teenagers to clean littered streets and alleys in the district.<ref name=prepareforwork /><ref>{{cite news |title=Capital's Eyesores Falls to Pride, Inc |date=August 9, 1967 |work=The Fort Scott Tribune |location=Fort Scott, Kansas |agency=Associated Press |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=U9gfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LtkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=986,4897448&dq=marion-barry+pride-inc&hl=en}}</ref> Barry and Treadwell had met while students at Fisk University, and they later met again while picketing in front of the Washington Gas Light Company.<ref name=marries>{{cite news |title= Marion Barry Marries |work= The Washington Post |first= Sally |last= Quinn |date= May 27, 1972 |page= B3 |id= {{ProQuest|148282440}} }}</ref>\n\nBarry and Treadwell married in 1972.<ref name=marries /> They separated five years later.<ref name=just />\n\nBarry was active in the aftermath of the [[1968 Washington, D.C. riots]] that followed the [[assassination of Martin Luther King, Jr.]] in Memphis. He organized through Pride Inc. a program of free food distribution for poor black residents whose homes and neighborhoods had been destroyed in the rioting. Barry convinced the [[Giant-Landover|Giant Food]] supermarket chain to donate food, and he spent a week driving trucks and delivering food throughout the city's housing projects. He also became a board member of the city's Economic Development Committee, helping to route federal funds and venture capital to black-owned businesses that were struggling to recover from the riots.<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nWhen President [[Richard Nixon]] declared July 21, 1969, National Day of Participation in honor of the moon landing by [[Apollo 11]], Barry criticized him. Barry believed that Dr. [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] deserved a national honor day on his birthday, which Nixon had opposed.<ref name=apollo>{{cite news |title= Barry Slams Apollo 11 Mission |first= Vincent |last= Paka |work= The Washington Post |page= A9 |date= July 19, 1969 |id= {{ProQuest|147633287}} }}</ref> Said Barry, \"Why should blacks feel elated when we see men eating on the moon when millions of blacks and poor whites don't have enough money to buy food here on earth?\"<ref name=apollo />\n\n==1971\u20131974: D.C. Board of Education==\nIn 1971, Barry announced his candidacy for [[at-large]] member of the [[board of education|school board]], running against the incumbent, Anita L. Allen.<ref name=barbs>{{cite news |title= Barry-Allen Barbs Fly in School Race |first1= Lawrence |last1= Feinberg |first2= Ivan C. |last2= Brandon |work= The Washington Post |date= September 10, 1971 |page= C1 |id= {{ProQuest|148180978}} }}</ref><ref name=sixseats>{{cite news |title= 31 File Petitions for Six Seats on Washington School Board |date= September 20, 1971 |page= C2 |work= The Washington Post |id= {{ProQuest|148003283}} }}</ref> Barry said he wanted to steer the school board back to the \"issues of education\" and away from problems of personalities.<ref name=barbs /> Barry defeated Allen, with 58 percent of the vote to Allen's 34 percent.<ref name=allen>{{cite news |title= Mrs. Allen, Allies Lose D.C. Vote |first= Richard E. |last= Prince |work= The Washington Post |date= November 3, 1971 |id= {{ProQuest|148122881}} }}</ref>\n\nAfter Barry was seated in 1972,<ref name=comeback /> he was unanimously elected as president of the board.<ref>{{cite news |title= School Board Elects Barry As President |first= Irna |last= Moore |date= January 25, 1972 |work= The Washington Post |id= {{ProQuest|148204550}} }}</ref> He served as board president for two years, reorganizing the school system's finances and building consensus on the board.\n\nIn response to the 1972 [[blaxploitation]] film ''[[Super Fly (1972 film)|Super Fly]]'', Barry quickly formed a protest group named Blacks Against Narcotics and Genocide (BANG). Barry said the film was harmful to black youth, and that it glorified drug abuse. BANG called for a boycott of the film.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Yts9jEMop0C&pg=PA156 |page=156 |title=At a Theater Or Drive-In Near You: The History, Culture and Politics of the American Exploitation Film |last=Clark |first=Randall |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=1995 |isbn=0815319517 |edition=revised}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19720922&id=CrczAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YTIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=3320,1681468 |date=September 22, 1972 |last=Tully |first=Andrew |newspaper=Lodi News-Sentinel |title=Capital Fare: It only hurts black kids |page=6 |access-date=March 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XZADAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA55 |page=55 |title=Criticism Mounts Over 'Super Fly' |date=September 28, 1972 |journal=Jet |volume=43 |number=1 |issn=0021-5996 |publisher=Johnson Publishing}}</ref>\n\nBarry advocated for a larger budget for education<ref>{{cite news |title= D.C. School Board Rescinds Budget Cut of Teaching Jobs |first= Andrew |last= Barnes |date= July 20, 1972 |work= The Washington Post |page= B1 |id= {{ProQuest|148299037}} }}</ref> and raises for teachers.<ref>{{cite news |title= Rally Planned |work= The Washington Post |date= September 27, 1972 |first= Bart |last= Barnes |id= {{ProQuest|148238588}} }}</ref> Barry also supported the appointment of [[Barbara Sizemore]] as the city's superintendent, making Washington, DC the country's first major city with a woman as School Board Superintendent.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. Barbara Sizemore New D.C. School Head |first=Larry |last=Brown |date=August 11, 1973 |work=Baltimore Afro-American |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lkxGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=deUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=922,1081088&dq=marion-barry+sizemore&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Senate held up annual payments to the district because of debate over whether the federal government should continue to pay for holding the district's partisan elections, Barry called for public hearings on the matter.<ref name=automatic>{{cite news |title= Automatic U.S. Payment For City Asked By Barry |work= The Washington Post |first=Richard E. |last= Prince |date= November 10, 1972 |id= {{ProQuest|148395466}} }}</ref> He also commented, \"Since it is a known fact that the majority makeup of an elected government will be black, the conferees' agreement indicates to me that some members of Congress are saying that black people cannot be fiscally responsible, and therefore, have to have a predominantly white Congress overseeing how our monies are spent.\"<ref name=automatic />\n\n==1974\u20131979: D.C. Council and shooting==\nUpon establishment of [[District of Columbia home rule|Washington's home rule]] in 1974, Barry was elected an at-large member of Washington's first elected [[city council]]. In that position, he served as chair of the District of Columbia Committee on Finance and Revenue. He was re-elected in 1976.\n\nWhile serving on the [[Council of the District of Columbia|D.C. City Council]], Barry was shot on March 9, 1977, by radical [[1977 Washington, D.C. attack and hostage taking|Hanafi Muslims]] (a breakaway sect of the [[Nation of Islam]]) when they overran the [[John A. Wilson Building|District Building]].<ref name=just /> Barry was shot near his heart<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/shooting.htm | title=Barry 'A Very Lucky Man'; Bullet Stopped Near Heart | first=Kathy | last=Sawyer |work=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 1977}}</ref> during the two-day [[1977 Washington, D.C. attack and hostage taking|1977 Hanafi Siege]] in which hostages were held by the terrorists. This was finally defused by the FBI and Muslim ambassadors.<ref>{{cite news |title=12 Hanafi Moslems Face Indictments |agency=Associated Press |date=May 6, 1977 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=3hBaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gUsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6770,784531&dq=marion+barry&hl=en}}</ref> Barry recovered from his injury.\n\n===1978 mayoral election===\n{{Main|Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1978}}\nHaving credentials as an activist, legislator, and \"hero\" in a hostage crisis, as well as an early endorsement from the ''Washington Post'',<ref name=78endors>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry for Mayor |author= editorial |work=The Washington Post |date=August 30, 1978 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/78endors.htm |access-date=November 19, 2010}}</ref> Barry was elected as mayor after [[Walter Washington]], the district's first mayor, fell out of political favor in the 1978 election.\n\nIn the Democratic primary\u2014the real contest in the heavily Democratic, black-majority city\u2014Barry ran with the campaign slogan \"Take a Stand\" and the promise to improve the \"bumbling and bungling\" Washington administration. He won the Democratic primary election against his main rivals Mayor Washington and council chairman [[Sterling Tucker]]. The vote was so close that final tally was in doubt for over two weeks.<ref name=wapo-1978-09-28>{{cite news |title=Mayor Says Barry Won D.C. Vote; Mayor Concedes Barry Victorious In District Voting |first=Paul W. |last=Valentine |work=The Washington Post |page=C1 |date=September 28, 1978 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/135572972.html?FMT=ABS |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> Barry defeated his Republican opponent [[Arthur Fletcher]] and two other minor candidates in a landslide general election in November.<ref name=wapo-1976-11-08>{{cite news |title=Barry Wins Mayor Race In a Breeze; Democrats Score Virtual Sweep to Retain Dominance Election '78/The District Barry Is Decisive Winner In Race for District Mayor |first=Milton |last=Coleman |author2=Bredemeier, Kenneth |work=The Washington Post |page=A1 |date=November 8, 1978 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/access/135607392.html?FMT=ABS |access-date=March 3, 2010}}</ref> He was the second person elected to the mayor's office.\n\n==1979\u20131991: Washington, D.C. Mayor==\n===First term===\nBarry's first four years in office were characterized by increased efficiency in city administration and government services, in particular the sanitation department. Barry also instituted his signature summer jobs program, in which summer employment was made available to every school-age resident. At the same time, Barry straightened the city's chaotic finances and attacked the deficit by introducing spending controls and laying off ten percent of the city's workforce.<ref name=tenure>{{cite news|title=Barry Brings Halt to Turbulent D.C. Saga/Barry's Tenure Was A Roller-Coaster Ride|first=Vernon|last=Loeb|work=The Washington Post|date=May 22, 1998|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barryyears0522b.htm|access-date=November 19, 2010}}</ref> Each year of his first term saw a budget surplus of at least [[United States dollar|US$]]13 million.<ref name=blackent>{{cite news|title=Washington: District of Commerce|last=Jones|first= Patricia A.|work=Black Enterprise|date=June 1986|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gwWMVXT0vcwC&pg=PA253&lpg=PA253&dq=%22Marion+Barry%22+surplus&source=bl&ots=bkUQMNDhE_&sig=IOcT8snxc5FcgaPH4B_R-QSnSp4&hl=en&ei=-mjlTKDyMoGClAfC7NTeCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCQQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q=%22Marion%20Barry%22%20surplus&f=false}}</ref> District of Columbia political reporter Jonetta Rose Barras characterized the first Barry administration as \"methodical, competent, and intellectually superior.\"<ref name=barras />\n\nHowever, unemployment rose dramatically during Barry's first administration, as did crime rates, in part because many of his layoffs were centered in the police department (1,500 terminations by 1981). His campaign promise to \"take the boards off\" public housing&nbsp;\u2013 ''i.e.'', to rehabilitate dilapidated and condemned public housing units&nbsp;\u2013 was slow in fulfillment. The city's debt was a constant problem as well: Barry had recalculated the Washington Administration's claim of a $41 million surplus and found that the city was $285 million in debt,<ref name=barras /> a long-term accrual that his annual surpluses were unable to surmount by the end of his term. Graft and embezzlement among Barry appointees, such as Employment Services director Ivanhoe Donaldson, began late in Barry's first term, although it would not be discovered for several years.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref name=1982endorse>{{cite news|title=The Next Mayor ...|work=The Washington Post|date=September 10, 1982|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/82endors.htm|access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Barry was personally touched by a number of \"mini-scandals\". He had travels with finances he often kept secret. He was first reported to be using [[cocaine]] at downtown nightclubs.<ref name=tenure />\n\n===Second term===\nIn 1982, Barry faced re-election against a challenge from fellow Democrat [[Patricia Roberts Harris]], an African-American woman who had served in two cabinet positions under President [[Jimmy Carter]], as well as from council members [[John L. Ray]] and [[Charlene Drew Jarvis]]. In the primary election held September 14, 1982, Barry won by a landslide, with over 58% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=429133|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor \u2013 D Primary Race \u2013 Sep 14, 1982|publisher=}}</ref> He won 82% of the vote in the November 11 general election against Republican candidate E. Brooke Lee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52605|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race|date=November 2, 1982|publisher=ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>\n\nBarry's second term was much more troublesome than his first. Though Washington experienced a massive real estate boom that helped alleviate the city's fiscal problems for a time,<ref name=making /> government spending skyrocketed; the administration posted a fifth straight budget surplus,<ref name=blackent /> but the next year struggled with a $110 million deficit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry's Chickens Prepare to Roost|first=Eric|last=Pianin|author2=Sherwood, Tom|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 19, 1983|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/84budget.htm}}</ref> Much of the disparity was caused by Barry's policy of combatting unemployment by creating government jobs; the city government's payrolls swelled so greatly that by 1986, nobody in the administration knew exactly how many employees it had.<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nWasteful contract spending also became a problem in the second Barry administration. In his first term Barry had made a point of insisting that any firm wishing to do business with the city have minority partners, and shepherding legislation requiring 35% of all contracts to go to minority-owned firms. The policy was modified in his second term such that the administration gave contracts to Barry's political connections and high-end campaign contributors to the tune of $856 million.<ref name=blackent /> The city did not exercise sufficient oversight. The cost of services such as heating oil for the public schools inflated 40 percent, without any guarantee that the goods and services were being provided. City councilman [[John A. Wilson (politician)|John A. Wilson]] commented that \"What started out to benefit the minority community at large has meant some politically influential blacks can move out to posh suburbs.\"<ref name=dreamcity />\n\nMajor scandal caught up to the mayor in his second term. Several of his associates were indicted for financial malfeasance, including former administration officials Ivanhoe Donaldson and Alphonse G. Hill. Barry began to be plagued by rumors and press reports of womanizing and of alcohol and drug abuse; in particular, stories abounded of his cocaine use in the city's nightclubs and red-light district. In 1983, Barry's ex-wife, Mary Treadwell, was convicted of fraudulently using federal funds given to Pride, Inc., a group that helped local youth find employment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Son of the soil, Barry had guts, guile on his side|work=Washington Times|first=Adrienne T.|last= Washington, DC|page=A5|date= January 19, 1990|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0EE9E70E560E7&p_docnum=12&p_queryname=24}}</ref> In 1984, Barry's one-time lover Karen Johnson was convicted of cocaine possession and contempt of court for refusing to testify to a grand jury about Barry's drug use.<ref name=timeline>{{cite news|title=The Barry Years: Triumphs and Troubles|first=Jane|last=Ashley |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=January 21, 1990|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/timeline.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Barry's second four years in office had some high points, including the District's entry into the open [[bond market]] with Wall Street's highest credit rating,<ref name=tenure /> and Barry's nomination speech for Jesse Jackson at the 1984 Democratic Convention.<ref name=timeline />\n\n===Third term===\nBarry sought a third term as mayor in 1986. By this time, his dominance of city politics was so absolute that he faced only token opposition in the Democratic primary in the form of former school board member Mattie Taylor, whom Barry dispatched rather easily. Barry had expected to face Jesse Jackson, who had been encouraged by colleagues to seek the mayoralty, and who had been relatively popular in stark contrast to Barry's declining reputation. Barry, who knew that most of Jackson's income came from delivering speeches, used his political clout to arbitrarily disqualify Jackson by getting a law passed that said anyone who made more than a certain amount in [[Honorarium|honoraria]] was ineligible to run for D.C. office. Council members jokingly called this the \"Jesse Jackson law,\" as it was legislated expressly to keep Jackson out of the mayoral race. As expected, Barry defeated Republican city councilwoman [[Carol Schwartz]] fairly handily in the November 4 general election. However, Schwartz managed to win 33 percent of the vote\u2014the first time a Republican had crossed the 30-percent barrier in a general election.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52604|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race \u2013 Nov 04, 1986|publisher=}}</ref> For the third time, Barry received the endorsement of ''The Washington Post'' but \"with far greater reservations and misgivings\" than at any time in the past.<ref name=1986endorse>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry for Mayor |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=November 2, 1986 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/86endors.htm |access-date=October 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy this time, Barry was openly suffering from the effects of longstanding addictions to cocaine and alcohol; he would later admit that he lost control of his drug habit soon after being sworn in for a third term.<ref name=dreamcity /> His public appearances were marked by his glassy eyes and slurred speech. His aides began scheduling all of his daily events later and later in the day as he was arriving to work as late as lunchtime, and nodding off to sleep at his desk. His ability to function as mayor had become so impaired that even his closest associates urged him not to run again. They tried to create an endowed professorship for him at the [[University of the District of Columbia]]. In the wake of Barry's inattention, the city declined badly. Barry was watching [[Super Bowl XXI]] in [[Pasadena, California]] when a winter blizzard struck Washington in January 1987; city crews were accused of badly mishandling the road clearing, adversely affecting local businesses.<ref name=dreamcity /><ref name=tenure />\n\nIn 1987 [[Crack cocaine|crack]] use exploded in the city,<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. Crime Prompts Request for More Officers |agency=Associated Press |date=February 20, 1989 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ez8gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XXoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6965,7011136&dq=marion-barry+homicide&hl=en}}</ref> as did territorial wars among drug dealers; in 1988 there were 369 homicides in Washington, D.C., the most ever in the city.<ref>{{cite news |title=Capital's Murder Toll Equals Record |agency=Associated Press |date=October 29, 1989 |location=Cape Girardeau, Missouri |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DFkfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ptgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3888,7526355&dq=marion-barry+murder+369&hl=en}}</ref> That record was broken when the next year had 434 homicides,<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. Is Murder Capital Again |agency=Associated Press |date=November 25, 1990 |location=Bend, Oregon |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CVYPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mIYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2749,704237&dq=marion-barry+murder+434&hl=en}}</ref> and it was broken again in 1990 with 474 homicides, making Washington's murder rate the highest in the nation. The Washington, D.C. government's employment and deficits grew as city services suffered; in particular, there were frequent press reports of deaths occurring because police lacked cars to get to crime scenes, and EMS services responded slowly or went to the wrong address.<ref name=barras /><ref name=dreamcity />\n\n===1990 arrest and drug conviction===\nBy late 1989, federal officials had been investigating Barry on suspicion of illegal drug possession and use; that fall, they prosecuted several of Barry's associates for cocaine use, including Charles Lewis, a native of the [[United States Virgin Islands]]. He was implicated in a drug investigation involving Barry and a room at Washington's [[Ramada|Ramada Inn]] in December 1988.\n\n[[File:Marion Barry smoking crack.gif|thumb|right|Barry captured on a surveillance camera smoking crack cocaine during a joint sting operation by the FBI and [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|D.C. Police]].]]\n\nOn January 18, 1990, Barry was arrested with a former girlfriend, Hazel Diane \"Rasheeda\" Moore, in a [[sting operation]] at [[The Westin Washington, D.C. City Center|the Vista International Hotel]] by the FBI and [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia|D.C. police]] for [[crack cocaine]] use and possession.<ref>{{cite news |title= Barry Arrested on Cocaine Charges in Undercover FBI, Police Operation |work= The Washington Post |date= January 19, 1990 |page= A1 |first= Sharon |last= LaFraniere |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/tours/scandal/barry.htm}}</ref> Moore was an FBI informant when she invited Barry to the hotel room and insisted that he smoke freebase cocaine before they had sex, while agents in another room watched on camera, waiting for Barry to accept her offer. During the videotaped arrest, Barry says of Moore, \"Bitch set me up...I shouldn't have come up here...goddamn bitch\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Jurors View Videotape of Barry Drug Arrest |work= The Washington Post |date= June 29, 1990 |page= A1 |first= Tracy |last=Thompson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/video.htm}}</ref>\n\nBarry was charged with three felony counts of perjury, 10 counts of drug possession, and one misdemeanor count of conspiracy to possess cocaine, even though the cocaine belonged to the government informant. The criminal trial ended in August 1990 with a conviction for only one possession incident, which had occurred in November 1989, and an acquittal on another. The jury [[hung jury|deadlocked]] on the remaining charges. Six or seven jurors (of whom two were white and the rest black) believed that the evidence against Barry was overwhelming and that he had displayed \"arrogance\" during the trial. Against these, five black jurors were convinced that the prosecution had falsified evidence and testimony as part of a racist conspiracy against Barry, and even disputed factual findings that had not been contested in court.<ref>{{cite news |first=Elsa |last=Walsh |author2=Barton Gellman |date=August 23, 1990|title=Chasm Divided Jurors in Barry Drug Trial|work=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/jurors.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Folks |title=Mistrial; Jurors falter on 12 of 14 counts |work=Washington Times |date=August 11, 1990 |agency=LexisNexis <!-- |access-date=February 10, 2009 -->}}</ref> After scolding the jurors for not following his instructions, presiding judge [[Thomas Penfield Jackson]] declared a [[Trial#Mistrials|mistrial]] on the remaining charges.\n\nAs a result of his arrest and the ensuing trial, Barry decided in June 1990 not to seek re-election as mayor.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Oreskes |title=After Barry, Uncertainty; Mayor's Move Brings Painful Era to Close |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE5D8163CF936A25755C0A966958260 |work=The New York Times |date=June 15, 1990 |access-date=July 7, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=File |title=Probation For Marion Barry |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1DC1331F933A25750C0A9609C8B63&scp=2&sq=Marion+Barry+drug&st=nyt |work=The New York Times |date=March 10, 2006 |access-date=February 12, 2008}}</ref> After his arrest and through his trial, Barry continued as mayor. He even ran as an independent for an at-large seat on the council against 74-year-old incumbent [[Hilda Mason]].<ref name=wapo-1990-08-30>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Files Petitions for Council Race; Mayor Plans to Appear on November Ballot as Independent\n| first=Mary Ann\n| last=French\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A10\n| date=August 30, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72611853.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> Mason, a former ally who had helped Barry recuperate after the 1977 shooting, took the challenge personally, saying, \"I do feel very disappointed in my grandson Marion Barry.\"<ref name=wapo-1990-10-22>{{cite news\n| title=Council Candidate Barry Finds a Skeptical Electorate; Mayor Hopes Loyalists Stay in His Corner\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 22, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72625885.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> Mason was endorsed by a majority of the council members<ref name=wapo-1990-10-17>{{cite news\n| title=Council Majority Endorses Mason to Block Barry's Bid\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 17, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72623623.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> and by [[Jesse Jackson]], who was running for [[Shadow congressperson|shadow senator]].<ref name=wapo-1990-10-26>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Hits 'Betrayal' By Jackson\n| first=Steve\n| last=Twomey\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=D01\n| date=October 26, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72626830.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nBarry was sentenced to six months in federal prison shortly before the November election,<ref name=wapo-1990-10-27>{{cite news\n| title=Barry Sentenced to 6 Months in Prison;Judge Says Mayor Gave Aid to Drug Culture'\n| first=Michael\n| last=York\n| author2=Thompson, Tracy\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=October 27, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72626231.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> which he lost&nbsp;\u2013 the first and only electoral loss of his career&nbsp;\u2013 receiving 20 percent of the overall vote, but doing well among the voters of Ward 8.<ref name=wapo-1990-11-07>{{cite news\n| title=D.C. Council; Wilson Elevated to Chairman; Cropp, Mason Beat Barry\n| first=Rene\n| last=Sanchez\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A31\n| date=November 7, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72629101.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref> His wife and son moved out of the house later that month.<ref name=wapo-1990-11-29>{{cite news\n| title=Effi Barry and Son Move Out of Home; Separation From Mayor Follows Her Hints of Shaky Marriage\n| first1=Michael\n| last1=Abramowitz\n| author2=Trescott, Jacqueline\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=A01\n| date=November 29, 1990\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/72632874.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 2, 2008\n}}</ref>\nIn October 1991, Barry surrendered himself at a [[Federal Correctional Complex, Petersburg|correctional facility]] in [[Petersburg, Virginia]]. While serving his time, Barry was accused of letting a woman perform oral sex on him in a prison waiting room,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Transferred to New Prison After Officials Confirm Sex Allegations |agency=Associated Press |date=January 11, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=y3UcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dGQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3480,3988739&dq=marion-barry+prison&hl=en}}</ref> a charge Barry denied.<ref name=cambria>{{cite news |title=Sex Charges Force Barry to U.S. Prison in Cambria |agency=Associated Press |date=January 12, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zHUcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dGQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5170,4128061&dq=marion-barry+prison+loretto&hl=en}}</ref> Barry was transferred to another [[Federal Correctional Institution, Loretto|federal prison]] in [[Loretto, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=cambria /> Barry was released in April 1992.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Released From Prison |agency=Associated Press |location=Dubuque, Iowa |date=April 23, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HWNFAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K7wMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3189,5209683&dq=marion-barry+prison+loretto+released&hl=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, after [[Toronto]] mayor [[Rob Ford]] was allegedly videotaped smoking what was reported to be crack,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2013/05/17/rob_ford_crack_scandal_mayor_must_respond_councillor_says.html|title=Rob Ford crack scandal: Toronto mayor refuses to discuss specifics of video|date=May 17, 2013|work=thestar.com}}</ref> parallels were made with the similarity to the 1990 incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/05/toronto-mayor-rob-ford-marion-barry-91554.html|title=Pundits see Ford-Barry connection|work=POLITICO}}</ref> Barry denied any similarity, stating: \"Unless he was entrapped by the government, it's not similar.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= Former Washington D.C. mayor denies any parallels between himself and scandal-plagued Rob Ford |work= National Post |date= May 17, 2013 |first= Tristin |last= Hopper |url= http://news.nationalpost.com/2013/05/17/marion-barry-denies-any-parallels-between-himself-and-rob-ford/}}</ref>\n\n==1992\u20131994: Political comeback==\n===D.C. Council===\nBarry was released from prison in 1992, and two months later filed papers to run for the Ward 8 city council seat in that year's election.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Plans on Seeking Council Seat |agency=Associated Press |location=Gadsden, Alabama |date=June 21, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BMMfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=W9gEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2085,2158233&dq=marion-barry&hl=en}}</ref> Barry ran under the slogan \"He May Not Be Perfect, But He's Perfect for D.C.\" He defeated the four-term incumbent, [[Wilhelmina Rolark]], in the Democratic primary, winning 70 percent of the vote, saying he was \"not interested in being mayor\",<ref>{{cite news\n| title=Former Mayor's Victory Worries Many in Capital\n| work=The New York Times\n| date=September 17, 1992\n| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE2DE1738F934A2575AC0A964958260\n| access-date=July 30, 2008\n}}</ref> and went on to win the general election easily.\n\n===1994 mayoral election===\n{{Main|Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 1994}}\nDespite his earlier statements to the contrary, observers of Barry's council victory expressed beliefs that he was laying ground for a mayoral run in 1994.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Takes Office As Supporters Cheer; Others on Council, School Board Sworn In |first=Rene |last=Sanchez |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 3, 1993 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-926624.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091036/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-926624.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Indeed, Barry fulfilled expectations when he formally announced his candidacy for mayor on May 21, 1994, and was immediately regarded as a serious challenge to the unpopular incumbent mayor, [[Sharon Pratt|Sharon Pratt Kelly]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry to Kick Off D.C. Comeback Campaign |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times |date=May 22, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4230125.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091058/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4230125.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Despite much opposition, including an abortive effort to recall his 1992 council election,<ref>{{cite news |title=Recall Effort Launched Against Marion Barry | first=Alvin |last=Peabody |publisher=Washington Informer |date=July 20, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2252941.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106102306/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2252941.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> Barry won a three-way Democratic primary contest for mayor with 48% of the vote on September 13, pushing Kelly into last place.<ref>{{cite news |title= Barry, Smith, Thomas win in primary|first=Janice |last=Frink Brown |work=Washington Afro-American |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2268923.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091113/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-2268923.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-11-05}}</ref> The victory, coming after Barry's videotaped crack use and conviction, shocked the nation, carrying front-page headlines in newspapers such as the ''Los Angeles Times'' and ''Boston Globe''.<ref name=barras />\n\nAn oft-repeated Barry quote came in the aftermath of his victory in the Democratic primary election, in which he counseled those voters who opposed his mayoral campaign to \"get over it.\"<ref>{{cite news |title='I'm the Best&nbsp;... for Washington'; On Day After, Barry Advises White Voters to Deal With Him |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 15, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-909572.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091203/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-909572.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThough facing a credible challenge from Republican councilmember Carol Schwartz, who received the endorsement of the ''Washington Post'',<ref>{{cite news |title=The Mayoralty Election |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=October 9, 1994 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-914953.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091149/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-914953.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> Barry was victorious in the general election with 56% to Schwartz's 42% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=52602|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 DC Mayor Race \u2013 Nov 08, 1994|publisher=}}</ref> Not only was this easily the strongest showing by a Republican mayoral candidate since the restoration of home rule, but it was also the first time since then that a Democratic candidate for mayor had dropped below the 60 percent mark. It would not occur again until [[Muriel Bowser]] won the [[Washington, D.C. mayoral election, 2014|2014 general election]] with 54% of the vote.\n\n==1995\u20131999: D.C. Mayor fourth term==\n[[File:Marion Barry, 1996 in Washington, D.C (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Barry in 1996]]\nBarry was sworn into office on January 2, 1995, and was almost immediately confronted with a financial crisis.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry's Fourth Term Off to a Rocky Start |first=Howard |last=Schneider |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 16, 1995 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-816501.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091216/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-816501.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> The budgetary problems of his previous administrations had only increased during Kelly's term, with city officials estimating a fiscal 1996 deficit between $700 million and $1 billion.<ref name=barras /> In addition, city services remained extremely dysfunctional due to mismanagement. One month into his term, Barry declared that the city government was \"unworkable\" in its present state and lobbied Congress to take over the areas of its operation that were analogous to typical state government functions.<ref>[http://www.davidcatania.com/publicdocuments/DC_budget_timeline.pdf Davidcatania.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317074803/http://www.davidcatania.com/publicdocuments/DC_budget_timeline.pdf |date=March 17, 2012}}</ref> [[Wall Street]], which Barry had convinced just after his election to continue investing in municipal bonds, reduced the city's credit rating to \"junk status.\"<ref name=barras /> Instead of implementing Barry's proposals, the newly Republican Congress (who had come to power on promises of decreasing federal spending) placed several city operations into receivership and created the [[District of Columbia Financial Control Board]] to assume complete authority over the city's day-to-day spending and finances, including overrule of the mayor's fiscal decisions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Congress Creates Board to Oversee Washington, D.C. |first=Michael |last=Janofsky |newspaper=The New York Times |date=April 8, 1995 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE7DB1739F93BA35757C0A963958260}}</ref>\n\nThe next two years were dominated by budgetary and policy battles between Barry and the control board&nbsp;\u2014 along with [[Chief financial officer|Chief Financial Officer]] [[Anthony A. Williams]]&nbsp;\u2014 for power over the District of Columbia's operation. The conflict was ultimately settled when in 1997 the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton Administration]] and [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Lauch Faircloth]] agreed on legislation that rescued the city from its financial crisis but stripped Barry of all authority (including hiring and firing) over nine district agencies, making them directly answerable to the control board. Barry was left with control of only the Department of Parks and Recreation, the public libraries, and the Board of Tourism, as well as the ceremonial trappings of his office&nbsp;\u2014 a condition he characterized \"a rape of democracy.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Reforms are certain to reshape life in D.C. |first=Vincent S. |last=Morris |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=July 31, 1997 |url= https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-56806634}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=DC and the Feds |publisher=National Public Radio |date=August 15, 1997 |url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1038794}}</ref>\n\nBarry declined to run for a fifth term in office in June 1998, stating his belief that Congress would not restore full home rule while he was mayor.<ref>{{cite news |title=Controversial D.C. Mayor Marion Barry Says He'll Call It Quits |agency= Associated Press |work=Los Angeles Sentinel |date=June 3, 1998 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-490575141.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105091400/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-490575141.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> He was succeeded by city CFO [[Anthony A. Williams]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n==2000\u20132014: D.C. Council==\n[[File:Marion Barry at 1998 St Patrick's Day Parade.jpg|thumb|Barry at the 1998 Washington, D.C. [[Saint Patrick's Day]] Parade]]\n\nAfter leaving office, Barry performed consulting work for an investment banking firm. On March 6, 2002, Barry declared his intention to challenge at-large council member [[Phil Mendelson]] in the Democratic primary.<ref name=wapo-2002-03-07>{{cite news\n| title=Barry to Heed 'Calling' With Bid for D.C. Council; Comeback Campaign Takes Aim at Mendelson\n| first=Craig\n| last=Timberg\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=B01\n| date=March 7, 2002\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/110223673.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 7, 2008\n}}</ref> Within a month, he decided against running, after an incident in which U.S. Park Police found traces of marijuana and cocaine in his car.<ref name=wapo-2002-04-05>{{cite news\n| title=Without Barry, the Plot Gets Thinner; Council Member Mendelson Loses a Key Foe, and Supporters Lose a Key Voice\n| first=Craig\n| last=Timberg\n| work=The Washington Post\n| page=B04\n| date=April 5, 2002\n| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/112946966.html?FMT=ABS\n| access-date=August 7, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, 2004, Barry announced that he was running in the Democratic primary for the Ward 8 council seat, a position he held before becoming mayor. Barry received 58% of the vote, defeating the incumbent council member, [[Sandy Allen (D.C. Council)|Sandy Allen]], on September 14, 2004.<ref name=2004p>{{cite web |title=Certified Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=September 14, 2004 |url=http://www.dcboee.org/information/elec_2004/sep14cr/En_W8_Council.shtm |access-date=December 3, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314151025/http://www.dcboee.org/information/elec_2004/sep14cr/En_W8_Council.shtm |archive-date=March 14, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barry received 95% of the vote in the general election, giving him a victory in the race to represent Ward 8 in the Council.<ref name=2004g>{{cite web|title=Certified Summary Results |work=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics |date=November 18, 2004 |url=http://www.dcboee.org/pdf_files/Summary_2.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725222439/http://www.dcboee.org/pdf_files/Summary_2.pdf |archivedate=July 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2006 mayoral election, Barry endorsed [[Adrian Fenty]] despite [[Linda W. Cropp|Linda Cropp]] hiring many members of Barry's former [[political machine]]. Barry has publicly clashed with Fenty over [[D.C. United]]'s proposed soccer stadium in Barry's Ward 8. Barry was the stadium's most outspoken supporter on the council, whereas Fenty attempted to distance himself from his initial support for the project.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Nakamura |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/12/AR2007091202445.html |title=Fenty Goes Fishing Around Poplar Point |work=The Washington Post |date=September 13, 2007 |page=B01}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2007, Marion Barry was chosen as one of fifty wax statues to debut in the Washington D.C. franchise of [[Madame Tussauds|Madame Tussauds Wax Museum]]. Barry was chosen by a majority of Washington residents and tourists from Tussauds' \"Top 10 Wish List,\" in a contest that pitted him against [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]], [[Al Gore]], [[Denzel Washington]], [[Carl Bernstein]], [[Halle Berry]], [[Martin Sheen]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Nancy Reagan]] and [[Oprah Winfrey]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Darragh |last=Johnson |author2=Roberts, Roxanne |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/17/AR2007071701643.html |title=Washington's Mayor for Life To Be Truly Immortalized&nbsp;\u2013\u2014in Wax |work=The Washington Post |date=July 18, 2007 |page=B01}}</ref>\n\nBarry ran for re-election in 2008 and easily held off all five challengers in the Democratic primary: Ahmad Braxton-Jones, Howard Brown, Chanda McMahan, Sandra Seegars and Charles Wilson.<ref name=dcboee-list-2008>{{cite web\n| title=List of Candidates in Ballot Order for the September 9, 2008 Congressional and Council Primary Election\n| url=http://www.dcboee.org/nws/pdf_files/pn_146.pdf\n| author=District of Columbia Board of Elections and Ethics\n| date=July 26, 2008\n| access-date=August 1, 2008\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080730181508/http://www.dcboee.org/nws/pdf_files/pn_146.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = July 30, 2008}}</ref> No Republican or [[D.C. Statehood Green Party|Statehood Green]] candidates filed to run in the Ward 8 council race.\n\n===Vote on gay marriage===\n{{See also|Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia}}\nIn May 2009, Barry voted against a bill committing Washington, D.C. to recognize [[same-sex marriage]]s performed elsewhere. During his 2008 reelection campaign, Barry had told members of the Gertrude Stein Democratic Club, the city's largest [[LGBT]] political group, \"I don't think you should make [supporting the bill] a [[Litmus test (politics)|litmus test]]. But if a bill like that were to come up, I would vote for it.\"<ref name=june2008speech>{{cite news |last=Chibarro Jr. |first=Lou |title=Marion Barry announces support for gay marriage: D.C. Council member breaks long silence on issue |work=Washington Blade |date=June 24, 2008 |url=http://www.washblade.com/thelatest/thelatest.cfm?blog_id=19248 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20080628222745/http://www.washblade.com/thelatest/thelatest.cfm?blog_id=19248 |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 28, 2008 |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> Following his May 2009 vote against recognizing gay marriages, Barry was criticized for what activists believed to be an apparent [[Flip-flop (politics)|flip-flop]].<ref name=moralcompass /> Councilman [[Phil Mendelson]] said he was surprised by the vote because Barry had signed on as a co-introducer of the marriage bill.<ref name=moralcompass>{{cite news|last=Chibarro Jr. |first=Lou |title=Barry warns of racial divide over marriage: After heated debate, Council votes 12\u20131 to recognize gay unions from other states |work=[[Washington Blade]] |date=May 8, 2009 |url=https://www.washblade.com/2009/5-8/news/localnews/14495.cfm |access-date=July 6, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611074054/http://www.washblade.com/2009/5-8/news/localnews/14495.cfm |archivedate=June 11, 2009}}</ref> Barry said his position had not changed and warned that the council needed to move slowly on this issue. Citing his belief that the local [[African Americans|African American]] community was overwhelmingly opposed to gay marriage, \"All hell is going to break loose\", Barry said. \"We may have a civil war. The black community is just adamant against this.\"<ref name=moralcompass /><ref name=may2009vote>{{cite news |last=Craig |first=Tim |title=Barry Warns of \"Civil War\" Over Gay Marriage |work=The Washington Post |date=May 5, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/05/barry_warns_of_civil_war_over.html |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Legal problems===\n====Failures to file tax returns and pay taxes====\nOn October 28, 2005, Barry pleaded guilty to the [[misdemeanor]] charges stemming from an IRS investigation. The mandatory drug testing for the hearing showed Barry as being positive for cocaine and marijuana. On March 9, 2006, he was sentenced to three years [[probation]] for misdemeanor charges of failing to pay federal and local taxes, and underwent drug counseling.<ref>{{cite news |first=Debbi |last=Wilgoren |author2=Woodlee, Yolanda |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/03/09/AR2006030900848.html |title=Barry Sentenced to Three Years of Probation |work=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |author2=Leonnig, Carol D |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/10/AR2006011002018.html |title=Barry Tested Positive for Cocaine Use In the Fall |work=The Washington Post |date=January 11, 2006 |page=A01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, federal prosecutors sought to have his probation revoked for failure to file his 2005 tax return. U.S. Magistrate Judge Deborah Robinson refused, saying that prosecutors had not proved that the failure was willful, even if Barry was aware he had missed the deadline.<ref name=avoids>{{cite news |title=Barry avoids prison in tax case |date=June 21, 2007 |work=The Washington Times |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/jun/21/barry-avoids-prison-in-tax-case/}}</ref> According to Judge Robinson, sentencing Barry to jail without proving that he willfully failed to file his taxes would contradict precedent set by the United States Supreme Court.<ref name=avoids />\n\n[[File:Marionbarry001.jpg|thumb|Barry in 2007]]\nOn February 9, 2009, prosecutors filed a motion in federal court to revoke Barry's probation for not filing his 2007 tax return, which violated his probation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Westley |title=Prosecutors: Jail ex-D.C. mayor Barry over taxes |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hbca1B6HG_Pll1HiP0eGOpHslkIQD968B8KG0 |agency=The Associated Press |work=Google News |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009}}</ref><ref name=wanttosend>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors Want to Send Barry to Jail |first=Will |last=Thomas |work=[[WTTG]] |publisher=Fox Television Stations, Inc. |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009 |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/020909_marion_barry_tax_issues}}</ref> According to one prosecutor, Barry has not filed his taxes eight of the last nine years.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prosecutors urge jail for Marion Barry |work=UPI via COMTEX |date=February 9, 2009 |access-date=February 10, 2009 |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/prosecutors-urge-jail-marion-barry/story.aspx?guid={E3EAB21A-5E6C-497D-9C13-0223F8345832}&dist=msr_1}}</ref> Barry said the reason he did not file his taxes is because of distractions from his medical problems, although he noted that there is \"no excuse\" for not filing.<ref name=kept /> In an interview, Barry said he had been undergoing four-hour [[dialysis|dialyses]] three times a week as treatment for a problem with his kidney.<ref name=kept>{{cite news |title=Barry Says Kidney Issues Kept Him From Filing Taxes |first=Martin |last=Weil |work=Washington Post |date=February 11, 2009 |page=B04 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/10/AR2009021003625.html}}</ref><ref name=offers>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Offers Excuse For Not Filing Tax Return |first=Brian |last=Johnson |work=[[WUSA-TV]] |date=February 11, 2009 |url=http://www.wusa9.com/rss/local_article.aspx?storyid=81365 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303235246/http://www.wusa9.com/rss/local_article.aspx?storyid=81365 |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref><ref name=offers /> At that point, a kidney donor had been identified, but the operation had yet to be scheduled.<ref name=offers /> On February 17, [[WTOP-FM]] reported that, according to Barry's attorney, Barry had filed his federal and District tax returns for 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Better late than never? Barry files 2007 taxes |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |date=February 17, 2009 |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=25&sid=1604045}}</ref> The same day, Barry was admitted to Howard University Hospital to prepare for a kidney transplant the next day.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry to Get Kidney Transplant |last=Stewart |first=Nikita; Harris, Hamil R |work=The Washington Post |date=February 19, 2009 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2009/02/report_barry_to_get_kidney_tra.html}}</ref> Barry was released from the hospital on February 27,<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry released from hospital |date=February 28, 2009 |work=Washington Times |url=http://washingtontimes.com/news/2009/feb/28/metro-briefs-95126010/}}</ref> but he was readmitted on March 2 due to large amounts of air in his abdominal cavity and also due to Barry's complaints of serious pains,<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Back In Hospital |first=Karen |last=GreyHouston |work=[[WTTG]] |publisher=Fox Television Stations, Inc. |date=March 4, 2009 |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/local/030409_barry_back_in_hospital}}</ref> both of which were caused by the combination of medications Barry was taking after the operation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry back in hospital, doing well |first=Elizabeth |last=Hillgrove |work=The Washington Times |date=March 5, 2009 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/05/barry-back-in-hospital-doing-well/}}</ref> Barry was released from the hospital on March 6.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Goes Home from Hospital |first=Matt |last=Ackland |date=March 6, 2009 |work=[[WTTG]] |url=http://www.myfoxdc.com/dpp/news/030609_marion_barry_released}}</ref> On April 17, 2009, the prosecution withdrew their request to revoke Barry's probation.<ref>{{cite news |title=CURL: Barry holds court on D.C. streets |date=April 17, 2009 |work=Washington Times |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/17/marion-barry-holds-court-on-the-streets-of-distric/}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2011, the Internal Revenue Service filed a notice of federal tax lien against Barry because of $3,200 of unpaid federal income taxes for 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=IRS files tax lien of more than $3,200 against Barry |first=Jim |last=McElhatton |work=The Washington Times |date=December 14, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/14/irs-files-tax-lien-against-barry-for-more-than-320/}}</ref> Barry attributed the lien to poor communication between the Internal Revenue Service and his representatives.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry: New tax lien a result of poor communication |first=Tom |last=Howell Jr |work=The Washington Times |date=December 15, 2011 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2011/dec/15/barry-new-tax-lien-result-poor-communication/}}</ref>\n\n====Alleged traffic violations====\nOn September 10, 2006, Barry was stopped by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]] Uniformed Division police officers after stopping at a green light and running a red light.<ref name=tickets>{{cite news |title=Secret Service Tickets Barry |last=Woodlee |first=Yolanda; Lengel, Allan |work=The Washington Post |date=September 11, 2006 |page=B08 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/10/AR2006091001028.html}}</ref><ref name=testifies>{{cite news |title=Secret Service Testifies Against Barry |first=Brett |last=Zongker |agency=The Associated Press |work=The Washington Post |date=June 12, 2007 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/12/AR2007061202438_pf.html}}</ref> According to a Secret Service spokesman, the police officers pulled over his car, smelled alcohol, and administered a [[Driving under the influence#Field sobriety testing|field sobriety test]].<ref name=tickets /> Barry was then taken to the U.S. Capitol Police station for a [[breathalyzer]] test.<ref name=tickets /> The Secret Service said that the breathalyzer test did not give an accurate reading, but Barry later said that it gave a successful reading of 0.02%, which is less than the legal limit of 0.08%.<ref name=tickets /> The police officers asked Barry to give a urine analysis, which Barry refused.<ref name=tickets /> The officers gave Barry a ticket for running a red light and failing to submit to a urine analysis.<ref name=tickets /> He was also charged with driving an unregistered vehicle and misuse of temporary tags.<ref name=former>{{cite news |title=Former D.C. Mayor Marion Barry Acquitted on Drunk Driving, Related Charges |work=Fox News |agency=Associated Press |date=June 13, 2007 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,282034,00.html |access-date=June 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070616164658/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,282034,00.html |archive-date=June 16, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Barry pleaded not guilty to the charges.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Pleads Not Guilty to DUI |first=Henri E. |last=Cauvin |work=The Washington Post |date=November 15, 2006 |page=B04 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/14/AR2006111400652_pf.html}}</ref> Prosecutors offered Barry a deal to drop the charge of driving under the influence in exchange for a guilty plea from Barry; he declined.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barry Rejects Offer, Maintains Innocence |first=Henri E. |last=Cauvin |work=The Washington Post |date=February 3, 2007|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/02/AR2007020200834.html}}</ref> A judge found him not guilty of the charges.<ref name=former />\n\nOn December 16, 2006, the [[United States Park Police|Park Police]] pulled over Barry for driving too slowly, which Barry later said was because he was trying to figure out where to enter an elementary school's parking lot for a nonprofit foundation's event.<ref name=delayed>{{cite news |title=Barry Says Park Police Delayed Him for 3 Hours |first=Yolanda |last=Woodlee |work=The Washington Post |date=December 19, 2006 |page=B06 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/18/AR2006121801223_pf.html}}</ref> After looking up Barry's record, the police officer told Barry that his license had been suspended and ticketed Barry for operating a vehicle on a suspended license, despite Barry's insistence to the contrary.<ref name=delayed /> Two days later, the D.C. Department of Motor Vehicles confirmed that Barry's license had not actually been suspended and said a computer glitch must have caused the error.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former D.C. Mayor Barry Alleges Improper Traffic Stop |work=Fox News |agency=Associated Press |date=December 19, 2006 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,237384,00.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613040415/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0%2C2933%2C237384%2C00.html |archivedate=June 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn August 2, 2014, Barry was in a traffic accident in the district, which his spokesperson blamed on a \"hypoglycemic attack\" due to his [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetes]]. At the time of the accident Barry had $2,800 in unpaid tickets for speeding and parking violations accumulated since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeBonis|first1=Mike|title=Marion Barry racked up $2,800 in unpaid tickets before Saturday night crash|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/marion-barry-racked-up-2800-in-unpaid-tickets-before-saturday-night-crash/2014/08/04/cd5ffed2-1c18-11e4-ae54-0cfe1f974f8a_story.html|website=www.washingtonpost.com|publisher=The Washington Post|access-date=August 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Conflict of interest: personal benefit from contract to girlfriend====\nOn July 4, 2009, Barry was taken into custody by the Park Police after political consultant Donna Watts-Brighthaupt, his ex-girlfriend, claimed he was [[stalking]] her.<ref name=july2009wapo>{{cite news |author=Tim Johnson |author2=Jenna Johnson |title=The Charge Against Barry: Stalking His Ex-Girlfriend |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 6, 2009 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/05/AR2009070501056.html |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> Barry was arrested and charged with \"[[misdemeanor]] stalking\". Following an interview with authorities, he was released on citation and told he must appear before the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]] on July 9.<ref name=july2009arrest>{{cite news |title=D.C.'s Marion Barry arrested again |work=[[CNN]] |date=July 5, 2009 |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/07/05/marion.barry.arrested/ |access-date=July 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name=july2009nyt>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry Charged With Stalking a Woman |work=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 5, 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/06/us/06barry.html?ref=global-home |access-date=July 6, 2009}}</ref> However, all charges were dropped on July 8.<ref name=chargesdropped>{{cite news |title=Stalking charges against Barry dropped |publisher=[[WTOP-FM|WTOP]] |date=July 9, 2009 |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=25&sid=1713945 |access-date=July 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAn investigative report by a special counsel said that Barry had personally benefited from a contract that he had awarded to his then-girlfriend Donna Watts-Brighthaupt.<ref name=bennett>{{cite news |title=Bennett report: Barry benefited from city contract obtained for ex-girlfriend |work=The Washington Post |first=Tim |last=Craig |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/2010/02/bennett_report_barry_benefited.html?wpisrc=nl_buzz}}</ref><ref name=report>{{cite news |title=Report of Investigation Pursuant to D.C. Council Resolution 18\u2013217 |work=Robert S. Bennett, Hogan & Hartson LLP, via The Washington Post |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/dc/bennettReport%20of%20Investigation%20Pursuant%20to%20DC%20Council%20Resolution%2018-217.pdf}}</ref> The report stated that Barry had awarded a contract to Watts-Brighthaupt, who then repaid money owed to Barry with the proceeds of the contract.<ref name=bennett /> When interviewed by the special counsel, Watts-Brighthaupt admitted to plagiarizing substantial portions of her study from a publicly available study by the United States Department of Education.<ref name=report /> The special counsel report also said that Barry had requested 41 [[earmark (politics)|earmarks]] in 2009 worth $8.4 million, some of which were paid to organizations \"rife with waste and abuse.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Report May Put Barry in Hot Water&nbsp;\u2013 Again |work=[[WRC-TV]] |agency=Associated Press |publisher=NBC |first=Tom |last=Sherwood |date=February 16, 2010 |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/politics/Report-Puts-Barry-in-Hot-Water-84480352.html}}</ref> The report also said that Barry had impeded the investigation by refusing to respond to questions and by telling witnesses not to respond to questions and not give subpoenaed documents to the special counsel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Barry violated city contract law |work=The Washington Times |date=February 16, 2010 |first=Joseph |last=Weber |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/feb/16/report-barry-violated-city-contract-law/?feat=home_top5_read}}</ref>\n\nBarry responded to the special counsel report by claiming he had violated no written rules or procedures on such contracts<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Ex-mayor violated laws |work=The Washington Times |date=February 17, 2010 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/feb/17/american-scene-94738815/}}</ref> and that there was no conflict of interest.<ref name=girlfriend>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry apologizes for contract to girlfriend |agency=Associated Press |work=The Washington Post |date=February 23, 2010 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/23/AR2010022303808.html}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> Barry apologized for his \"very, very poor judgment.\"<ref name=girlfriend />\n\nIn response to the special counsel's report, several council members said they would like to hear a response from Barry before considering a [[censure]]. On March 2, 2010, the Council of the District of Columbia voted 12\u20130 in favor of stripping Barry of all committee assignments, ending his chair of the Committee on Housing and Workforce Development, and removing him from the Committee on Finance and Revenue.<ref>{{cite news |title=D.C. might censure Marion Barry over alleged corruption |first=Tim |last=Craig |work=The Washington Post |date=February 18, 2010 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/02/17/AR2010021704770.html}}</ref>\n\n===Asian American racist remarks controversy===\nAt a party celebrating his primary victory for his D.C. council seat on April 3, 2012, Barry said, \"We've got to do something about these Asians coming in, opening up businesses, those dirty shops. They ought to go, I'll just say that right now, you know. But we need African-American businesspeople to be able to take their places, too.\"<ref name=\"Asian Businesses Ought to Go\">{{cite news|last=DeBonis|first=Mike|title=UPDATE: Marion Barry apologizes for anti-Asian remarks|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/mike-debonis/post/marion-barry-stands-by-remark-that-asian-businesses-ought-to-go-from-ward-8/2012/04/05/gIQAP2TlxS_blog.html?hpid=z2|access-date=April 5, 2012|work=The Washington Post|date=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other council members, Mayor [[Vincent C. Gray|Vincent Gray]], and Delegate [[Eleanor Holmes Norton]] criticized Barry's comments.<ref name= deplorable>{{cite news |title=Outcry Over Barry's 'Deplorable' Comments Is Quick and Harsh |work= The Washington Times |date=April 5, 2012 |first=Tom |last= Howell Jr. |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/apr/5/outcry-over-barrys-deplorable-comments-is-quick-an/?page=all}}</ref> Five Asian American members of the Maryland General Assembly also called on Barry to apologize in a statement, saying, \"At best, Mr. Barry's attack on Asian Americans is deeply troubling, and at worst it is race baiting.\"<ref name=wtop2012>{{cite news |title=Barry Apologizes for Disparaging Comments About Asians |date=April 5, 2012 |work=[[WTOP-FM]] |url=http://www.wtop.com/?nid=41&sid=2816672}}</ref>\n\nBarry apologized for his comments, saying in a written statement, \"It is to these less than stellar Asian-American businessmen in Ward 8 that my remarks were directed, not the whole of Asian businessmen in Ward 8 or the Asian-American population.\"<ref name= deplorable />\n\nWhile apologizing to Asian Americans, Barry used the anti-Polish slur [[Polack]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-05-24/local/35457530_1_marion-barry-asian-community-asian-american | work=The Washington Post | first=Paul | last=Schwartzman | title=Marion Barry commits new gaffe while apologizing to Asians | date=June 20, 2012 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123140441/http://articles.washingtonpost.com/2012-05-24/local/35457530_1_marion-barry-asian-community-asian-american | archivedate=January 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarry married Effi Slaughter, his third wife, just after announcing his candidacy for mayor in 1978. The couple had one son, [[Marion Christopher Barry]], who died of a drug overdose on August 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marion Barry's son scheduled to be sentenced in drug case |first=Maggie |last=Fazeli Fard |date= September 27, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/crime-scene/post/marion-barrys-son-to-be-sentenced-in-drug-case/2011/09/27/gIQA8eDQ1K_blog.html}}</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=barry&GSfn=marion+&GSmn=christopher&GSbyrel=all&GSdyrel=all&GSob=n&GRid=173370805&df=all& Marion Christopher Barry, memorial; findagrave.com] Retrieved May 21, 2017</ref> The Barrys separated in November 1990, soon after he was caught on videotape smoking crack cocaine with an ex-model and propositioning her for sex.<ref>{{cite news |title=Effi Barry and Son Move Out of Home; Separation From Mayor Follows Her Hints of Shaky Marriage |last1= Abramowitz |first1= Michael |last2= Trescott |first2= Jacqueline |work= The Washington Post |date= November 29, 1990 |page=A1}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Barry's ex-wife, 63, dies of leukemia: Praised for public-health work |work= The Washington Times |date= September 7, 2007 |page= B1 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=11B86DF574909AA0&p_docnum=5&p_queryname=29}}</ref> They divorced in 1993, but she returned to Washington and supported him in his successful bid for a city council seat in 2004. Effi died on September 6, 2007, after an 18-month battle with [[acute myeloid leukemia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Effi Barry to Lie in Repose at Wilson Building |first=Nikita |last=Stewart |work=The Washington Post |date=September 8, 2007 |page=B02 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/07/AR2007090701833_pf.html}}</ref>\n\nBarry married Cora Masters on January 8, 1993.<ref name= towed>{{cite news |title= Barry to Wed |work= The Cincinnati Post |date= December 14, 1993 |page= 14A |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0312B2FD03223&p_docnum=23&p_queryname=34}}</ref> Masters was a political science professor at the [[University of the District of Columbia]]<ref name= towed /> and his former spokeswoman.<ref>{{cite news |title= A matter of perks: Foes hit Barry for using official car in his campaigning |work= The Washington Times |date= October 25, 1990 |first= Pam |last= McClintock |page= B1 |url= http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB0EEFBCE6ABA1D&p_docnum=1&p_queryname=35}}</ref> Barry's mother, Mattie Cummings, died at age 92 in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]] on November 8, 2009.<ref name=cummings>{{cite news |title=Mattie Cummings, 92; mother of D.C. Council's Marion Barry |first=Adam |last=Bernstein |date=November 11, 2009 |work=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/10/AR2009111018651.html}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Mayor Marion Barry's Memorial at Congressional Cemetery.jpg|thumb|Barry's memorial at [[Congressional Cemetery]]]]\nBarry died at United Medical Center in Washington, D.C., on November 23, 2014, from [[cardiac arrest]], aged 78.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wusa9.com/story/news/local/dc/2014/11/23/marion-barry-dies-78-years-old/19437553/|title=Marion Barry dies at 78|publisher=WUSA9.com|access-date=November 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141127155320/http://www.wusa9.com/story/news/local/dc/2014/11/23/marion-barry-dies-78-years-old/19437553/|archive-date=November 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|author1=David Stout|title=Marion Barry, Washington's 'Mayor for Life,' Even After Prison, Dies at 78|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/24/us/politics/marion-s-barry-jr-former-mayor-of-washington-dies-at-78.html?_r=0|access-date=November 27, 2014|work=NY Times|publisher=NYT|date=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name=wsj>{{cite news|first1=Rebecca |last1=Ballhaus |first2=Stephen |last2=Miller|title=Marion Barry, Former Washington Mayor, Dies at 78|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/former-washington-mayor-marion-barry-dies-at-78-1416730815|access-date=November 27, 2014|work=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Dow Jones & Co|date=November 24, 2014}}</ref> Following three days of memorial observances, he was buried December 6 at Washington's [[Congressional Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mike DeBonis|title=Marion Barry's final farewell draws thousands, stretches for hours|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/marion-barrys-final-farewell-draws-thousands-stretches-for-hours/2014/12/06/41b8fd24-7b00-11e4-84d4-7c896b90abdc_story.html?tid=ptv_rellink|access-date=December 8, 2014|work=Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post|date=December 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA private monument to Barry was erected over his grave and unveiled on November 22, 2016. The event was attended by current and former D.C. Council members, former mayor Sharon Pratt Kelly, and about 150 other dignitaries, family members, and friends of Barry. The memorial, conceived and largely designed by Cora Masters Barry and Marion Christopher Barry, was carved by nationally prominent sculptor and engraver Andy Del Gallo and manufactured by Eastern Memorials (a D.C.-based funerary monument company).<ref>{{cite news|last=Jamison|first=Petr|title=Capturing Marion Barry's complicated legacy in black granite|work=The Washington Post|date=November 23, 2016|access-date=November 24, 2016|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/capturing-marion-barrys-complicated-legacy-in-black-granite/2016/11/23/5562f4ec-b032-11e6-be1c-8cec35b1ad25_story.html}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn June 2009, a documentary of Barry's life was released at Silverdocs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/17/AR2009061703642.html|title=HBO Documentary 'The Nine Lives of Marion Barry' Will Be Featured at Silverdocs|last=Fisher|first=Marc|date=June 18, 2009|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=March 22, 2016}}</ref> The HBO Documentary was released on August 2009, on HBO.\n\nIn the midst of a [[Newark mayoral election, 2014|contentious mayoral race]] in [[Newark, New Jersey]] in May 2014, [[Rutgers University]] professor and Newark city historian Clement A. Price cited Barry and [[Jackson, Mississippi]]'s [[Chokwe Lumumba]] as his role models as mayor. The citation came in an April 2014 public discussion. Professor Price had not taken sides in the 2014 contest.<ref>Zernike, Kate, [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/09/nyregion/newark-mayoral-race-seen-as-referendum-on-booker.html \"Newark Mayoral Race Seen as Referendum on Booker\"], New York ''Times'', May 8, 2014. Retrieved May 11, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Marion Barry}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[List of Alpha Phi Alpha brothers]]\n* [[List of Eagle Scouts]]\n* [[List of mayors of Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[List of members of the Council of the District of Columbia]]\n* ''[[The Nine Lives of Marion Barry]]''\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite news |last=Dolan |first=Michael |url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/5546/visible-man |title= Visible Man: Can Marion Barry survive salvation? |work=[[Washington City Paper]] |date=January 6, 1995 |access-date=March 16, 2017}}\n*{{cite news |last=Marchenese |first=Kira |last2=Segan |first2=Sascha |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/longterm/library/dc/barry/barry.htm |title=Marion Barry: Making of a Mayor |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 21, 1998 |access-date=November 23, 2014}}\n*{{cite journal |title=Marion Barry: some notes |journal=The Progressive Review |last=Smith |first=Sam |year=1998 <!-- |access-date=August 2, 2008 -->}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.dcwatch.com/mayor/980521.htm |title=The Barry Years: 40 Years of Committed Public Service |work=DCWatch |date=May 21, 1998